{"title_page": "Mateusz Morawiecki", "text_new": "{{short description|17th Prime Minister of Poland}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Mateusz Morawiecki\n| image = Mateusz Morawiecki Prezes Rady Ministr\u00f3w (cropped).jpg\n| office = 17th [[Prime Minister of Poland]]\n| president = [[Andrzej Duda]]\n| deputy = [[Piotr Gli\u0144ski]]<br>[[Jaros\u0142aw Gowin]]<br>[[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]<br>[[Jacek Sasin]]\n| term_start = 11 December 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Deputy Prime Minister of Poland]]\n| 1blankname1 = Served with\n| 1namedata1 = {{Ublist|[[Piotr Gli\u0144ski]]<br/>[[Jaros\u0142aw Gowin]]}}\n| primeminister1 = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| term_start1 = 16 November 2015\n| term_end1 = 11 December 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Janusz Piechoci\u0144ski]]\n| successor1 = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Minister of Finance]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| term_start2 = 28 September 2016\n| term_end2 = 9 January 2018\n| predecessor2 = [[Pawe\u0142 Sza\u0142amacha]]\n| successor2 = [[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Teresa Czerwi\u0144ska]]\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Minister of Development]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| term_start3 = 16 November 2015\n| term_end3 = 9 January 2018\n| predecessor3 = [[Maria Wasiak]]\n| successor3 = [[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Jerzy Kwieci\u0144ski]]\n| birth_name = Mateusz Jakub Morawiecki\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|06|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Wroc\u0142aw]], [[Polish People\u2019s Republic|Poland]]\n| death_place = \n| party = [[Law and Justice]] (2016\u2013present)<br>[[Independent politician|Independent]] (before 2016)\n| spouse = Iwona Morawiecka\n| occupation = Economist, historian, magazine editor, politician\n| children = 4\n| relatives = [[Kornel Morawiecki]] {{small|(Father)}}\n| education = [[University of Wroc\u0142aw]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Wroc\u0142aw University of Science and Technology]]<br>[[Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics]] {{small|([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])}}<br>[[University of Hamburg]]<br>[[University of Basel]] {{small|([[Master of Advanced Studies|MAS]])}}\n| signature = Mateusz Morawiecki's signature 2017.jpg\n| website = www.premier.gov.pl\n}}\n\n'''Mateusz Jakub Morawiecki''' ({{small|Polish pronunciation:}} {{IPAc-pl|m|\u0254|r|a|v|i|\u02c8|\u025b|ts|k|\u02b2|i}}; born 20 June 1968) is a [[Poles|Polish]] [[economist]], [[historian]], and [[politician]] who has been the [[Prime Minister of Poland]] since December 2017. He previously served in the [[Cabinet of Beata Szyd\u0142o|Cabinet]] of Prime Minister [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]] as [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Deputy Prime Minister]] from 2015 to 2017, [[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Minister of Finance]] from 2016 to 2018, and [[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Minister of Development]] between 2015 and 2018. Prior to his political appointment, Morawiecki had an extensive business career. \n\nBorn in [[Wroc\u0142aw]], Morawiecki became heavily engaged in anti-communist movements in his youth. He attended the [[University of Wroc\u0142aw]] and extended his education at the [[University of Hamburg|Universities of Hamburg]] and [[University of Basel|Basel]]. He obtained degrees in arts, business administration, and advanced studies. From 1996 to 2004, Morawiecki lectured at the [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics]], as well as from 1996 to 1998 at the [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology]]. From November 1998, Morawiecki worked for [[Bank Zachodni WBK]] from the [[Banco Santander|Santander Group]], where he was promoted to the position of managing director and eventually chairman.\n\nOn 11 December 2017, Morawiecki was nominated as Prime Minister of Poland (''premier'') by the chief staff of the ruling [[Law and Justice]] party.\n\n==Early life and education ==\nMateusz Morawiecki was born 20 June 1968 in [[Wroc\u0142aw]], southwest Poland, to [[Kornel Morawiecki]], physicist and [[Fighting Solidarity]] leader, and his wife Jadwiga. Morawiecki is of distant [[Germans|German]] descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wprost.pl/tygodnik/10103523/rodzinna-lustracja-premiera.html|title=Rodzinna lustracja premiera|date=February 11, 2018|website=Wprost}}</ref> The [[Times of Israel]] also reported in 2017 that Morawiecki has \"Jewish roots\", however this claim has not been confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/poland-appoints-ex-banker-with-jewish-roots-as-prime-minister/|title=Poland appoints ex-banker with Jewish roots as prime minister|author=JTA|newspaper=Times of Israel|date=8 December 2017|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt age 12<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazetaprawna.pl/artykuly/1090531,kim-jest-mateusz-morawiecki.html|title=Kim jest kandydat na premiera Mateusz Morawiecki [SYLWETKA]|website=www.gazetaprawna.pl}}</ref> Morawiecki was already active in the Polish [[anti-communism|anti-communist]] movement, duplicating illegal political leaflets. In August 1980 he posted a poster edition of the ''Lower Silesia Bulletin'' all over [[Wroc\u0142aw]]. The poster listed the [[Gda\u0144sk Agreement#List of Points|Gda\u0144sk Demands]] and, in their support, called for a general strike on Poland's [[Baltic Sea]] coast. After [[Martial law in Poland|martial law]] was declared in 1981, he printed and distributed underground [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] magazines.\n\nHe publicly confessed to terrorist activities in the 1980s. Together with a group of friends, he was supposed to throw Molotov cocktails at police cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wprost.pl/polityka/10297541/morawiecki-o-czasach-prl-rzucalem-koktajlami-molotowa-do-tej-pory-koledzy-wspominaja-moje-poranione-plecy.html|title=Morawiecki o czasach PRL: Rzuca\u0142em koktajlami Mo\u0142otowa (...) do tej pory koledzy wspominaj\u0105 moje poranione plecy|last=WPROST.pl|date=2020-02-11|website=Wprost|language=pl|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nDespite repeated arrests and beatings by Poland's Security Service (''[[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa]]'', ''SB''), until the late 1980s he continued taking part in political demonstrations. He edited the ''Lower Silesia Bulletin'' and was active in the Independent Students' Association. In 1988 and 1989 he participated in occupation strikes at the University of Wroclaw. He co-organized the Club for Political Thought, \"Free and Solidary\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://kobieta.onet.pl/w-domu-nigdy-o-tym-nie-opowiadal-nie-chcial-martwic-matki-dziecinstwo-premiera/bt99r3q |title=\"W domu nigdy o tym nie opowiada\u0142. Nie chcia\u0142 martwi\u0107 matki\". Dzieci\u0144stwo premiera wspomina jego mama |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMorawiecki is an alumnus of the [[University of Wroc\u0142aw]] (history, 1992), [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology]] (1993), [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics]] ([[Business Administration]], 1995), the [[University of Hamburg]] (European Law and Economic Integration, 1995\u201397), and the [[University of Basel]] ([[European Studies]], 1995\u201397). While at the Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology, he studied abroad at [[Central Connecticut State University]] and completed an advanced executive program at [[Northwestern University]]'s [[Kellogg School of Management]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://oko.press/ludzie/morawiecki-mateusz/ |title=Mateusz Morawiecki |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premier.gov.pl/ludzie/mateusz-morawiecki.html |title=Mateusz Morawiecki |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nIn 1991 Morawiecki began work at Cogito Company and co-created two publishing firms, Reverentia and Enter Marketing-Publishing. That same year he co-founded the magazine ''Dwa Dni'' (Two Days), later becoming editor-in-chief. \n\nIn 1995 he completed an [[internship]] at [[Deutsche Bundesbank]] in credit analysis, financial restructuring, banking supervision, and financial market supervision. In 1996\u201397 he conducted banking and macroeconomic research at the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|University of Frankfurt]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bruegel.org/author/mateusz-morawiecki/ |title=Mateusz Morawiecki |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> In 1998, as deputy director of the Accession Negotiations Department in the Committee for European Integration, he oversaw and participated in numerous areas, including finance, of the negotiations for [[Poland in the European Union|Polish accession to the European Union]]. \n\nWith Frank Emmert, he co-authored the first textbook on ''The Law of the European Union'' published in Poland.\n\nFrom 1996 to 2004 Morawiecki lectured at the [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics]], and from 1996 to 1998 also at the [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology]]. He sat on policy committees at many institutions of higher education. From 1998 to 2001 he was a member of the supervisory boards of the Wa\u0142brzych Power Company, Dialog (a local telephone-service provider), and the Industrial Development Agency. From 1998 to 2002 he was a member of the [[Lower Silesian Regional Assembly]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.umwd.dolnyslask.pl/sejmik/radni-wojewodztwa/radni-i-kadencji/ |title=I Kadencja Sejmiku Wojew\u00f3dztwa Dolno\u015bl\u0105skiego |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom November 1998 Morawiecki worked for [[Bank Zachodni WBK]], [[Banco Santander|Santander Group]], where he began his career as deputy chair of the supervisory board, and supervisor of the economic analysis bureau and the international trade department. In 2001 he became managing director and a member of the board. In 2007\u201315 Morawiecki was chairman of [[Bank Zachodni WBK]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wprost.pl/tematy/10126719/mateusz-morawiecki.html |title=Mateusz Morawiecki |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Mateusz Morawiecki na otwarciu Campus Warsaw.jpg|thumb|left|upright 1.0|Morawiecki at opening of Campus Warsaw]]\nOn 16 November 2015, President [[Andrzej Duda]] appointed Mateusz Morawiecki as both [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Deputy Prime Minister]] and [[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Minister of Development]] in the Cabinet led by Prime Minister [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116143425/http://www.prezydent.pl/aktualnosci/nominacje/art,3,prezydent-powolal-rzad.html|title=Oficjalna strona Prezydenta Rzeczypospolitej Polskiej / Aktualno\u015bci / Nominacje / Prezydent powo\u0142a\u0142 rz\u0105d|date=2015-11-16|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref> (This took place soon after Mateusz Morawiecki's father, [[Kornel Morawiecki]], was elected to Poland's lower chamber of the parliament<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sejm.gov.pl/Sejm8.nsf/posel.xsp?id=255&type=A|title=Kornel Morawiecki|website=sejm.gov.pl|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref> and the [[Law and Justice]] party won the [[2015 Polish parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary elections]].)\n\nIn March 2016, Mateusz Morawiecki announced that he had joined the Law and Justice party.\n\nOn 28 September 2016, in addition to his other positions, Morawiecki was appointed [[Minister of Finance (Poland)|Minister of Finance]], becoming the second most powerful member of the Government, overseeing the budget, government finances, [[European Union]] funds, and overall economic policy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/polish-reshuffle-puts-sights-on-prime-minister/ |title=Polish reshuffle puts sights on prime minister |publisher=POLITICO |date=29 September 2016 |accessdate=21 October 2016 |language=en }}</ref>\n\nAs Finance Minister, Morawiecki outlined an ambitious \"Plan for Responsible Development\", known colloquially as the \"Morawiecki Plan\", aimed at stimulating economic growth and raising revenues for generous government plans, including \u201cFamily 500+\u201d child benefits for all families with two or more children.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/12/Artykul/273305,Trillions-needed-to-modernise-Poland-deputy-minister|title=Trillions needed to modernise Poland: deputy minister|publisher=Radio Poland |date=30 September 2016 |accessdate=21 October 2016 |language=en }}</ref> In March 2017, he took part in a meeting of [[G20]] finance ministers in [[Baden-Baden]], becoming Poland's first-ever representative at that summit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rp.pl/Gospodarka/303169812-Morawiecki-wsrod-ministrow-finansow-G20.html#ap-1|title=Morawiecki w\u015br\u00f3d ministr\u00f3w finans\u00f3w G20 - Gospodarka - rp.pl|access-date=2017-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tvn24bis.pl/ze-swiata,75/rzeczy-ktore-musisz-wiedziec-o-szczycie-g20,724315.html|title=Rzeczy, kt\u00f3re musisz wiedzie\u0107 o szczycie G20 {{!}} Ze \u015bwiata|work=TVN24 BiS|access-date=2017-03-31|language=pl}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Poland==\n[[File:Premier Mateusz Morawiecki na spotkaniach Grupy Wyszehradzkiej przed szczytem Rady Europejskiej (38167092585).jpg|thumb|Morawiecki with [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] (V4) leaders and [[President of the European Commission|European Commission President]] [[Jean Claude Juncker]], Brussels 2017]]\n\nIn December 2017, [[Jaros\u0142aw Kaczy\u0144ski]], the Chairman of the Law and Justice party, declared that he no longer had confidence in Beata Szyd\u0142o to be the party's prime ministerial candidate, in part due to perceived conflict between her and other European Union leaders. With her position untenable, Szyd\u0142o resigned, and Morawiecki quickly won internal party approval to be nominated as her successor. He was sworn in as [[Prime Minister of Poland]] on 11 December, immediately appointing Szyd\u0142o as his deputy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Komitet Polityczny PiS desygnowa\u0142 Mateusza Morawieckiego na Premiera|url=http://pis.org.pl/aktualnosci/komitet-polityczny-pis-desygnowal-mateusza-morawieckiego-na-premiera|website=Prawo i Sprawiedliwo\u015b\u0107|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> In his first major address to [[Sejm]], he pledged \u201ccontinuity\u201d rather than radical change.<ref>Micha\u0142 Broniatowski (December 12, 2017), [https://www.politico.eu/article/poland-new-prime-minister-mateusz-morawiecki-wont-change-anything-after-leadership-swap/ Poland\u2019s new PM won\u2019t change anything after leadership swap] ''[[Politico Europe]]''.</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, following a highly public [[racist]] incident in [[Warsaw]], Morawiecki declared: \"There is no place in Poland for racism. The attack on a girl because of her skin color deserves the strongest condemnation. We shall do everything to make Poland safe for everyone.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=No place for racism in Poland, says PM after attack on teen|url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/342885,No-place-for-racism-in-Poland-says-PM-after-attack-on-teen|website=Radio Poland|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, both chambers of the Polish parliament (the [[Sejm]] and [[Senate of Poland|Senate]]) adopted an [[Amendment to the Act on the Institute of National Remembrance]] criminalising the ascription to Poles collectively of complicity in [[World War II]] [[Holocaust|Jewish-genocide]]-related or other [[war crime]]s or [[crimes against humanity]] that had been committed by the [[Axis powers]], and condemning use of the expression, [[\"Polish death camp\" controversy|\"Polish death camp\"]].<ref name=\"wapo20180127\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/01/27/it-could-soon-be-a-crime-to-blame-poland-for-nazi-atrocities-and-israel-is-appalled/  Israel and Poland try to tamp down tensions after Poland\u2019s \u2018death camp\u2019 law sparks Israeli outrage], Washington Post, 28 January 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-poland/israel-and-poland-clash-over-proposed-holocaust-law-idUSKBN1FH0S3 Israel and Poland clash over proposed Holocaust law], Reuters, 28 January 2018</ref><ref name=\"SmithsonianJan2018\">[https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/poland-grants-initial-approval-controversial-death-camp-bill-180967975/ The Controversy Around Poland\u2019s Proposed Ban on the Term \u201cPolish Death Camps\u201d], Smithsonian.com, 29 January 2018</ref> The law sparked a crisis in [[Israel\u2013Poland relations]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/latest-poland-reverses-disputed-holocaust-law-56194754|title=The Latest: Party head: Israel confirms Polish view on Nazis|last=News|first=ABC|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en}}</ref>  \n\n[[File:Angela Merkel i Mateusz Morawiecki.JPG|thumb|left|Morawiecki with [[Angela Merkel]], [[Berlin]], February 2018]]\n\nAt the Munich Security Conference on 17 February that year, Morawiecki said \"it is not going to be seen as criminal to say that there were Polish perpetrators, as there were [[Jews|Jewish]] perpetrators, as there were [[Russians|Russian]] perpetrators, as there were [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] perpetrators, not only [[Germans|German]] perpetrators.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/poland-mateusz-morawiecki-israel-netanyahu-holocaust-jewish-perpetrators/|title=\"Jewish perpetrators\" remark reignites Poland Holocaust dispute|date=19 February 2018|work=CBS News}}</ref><ref name=\"jpost\">{{cite news |title=Polish MP: I hope my prime minister is being stupid and not ruthless |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Polish-MP-I-hope-my-prime-minister-is-being-stupid-and-not-ruthless-542986 |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=19 February 2018}}</ref> His remark roused controversy and prompted criticism by prominent Israeli politicians, including [[Israel|Israeli]] Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/poland-mateusz-morawiecki-israel-netanyahu-holocaust-jewish-perpetrators/|title=\"Jewish perpetrators\" remark reignites Poland Holocaust dispute|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/benjamin-netanyahu-mateusz-morawiecki-jews-perpetrators-holocaust-munich-security-conference-a8216421.html Benjamin Netanyahu attacks Polish PM for saying Jews were among perpetrators of the Holocaust]\". ''The Independent.'' 18 February 2018.</ref> and Israeli President [[Reuven Rivlin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/polish-embassy-in-israel-vandalized-after-polish-pm-controversial-remarks/4260010.html|title=Polish Embassy in Israel Vandalized After Polish PM's Controversial Remarks|date=18 February 2018|work=VOA News}}</ref> The crisis was resolved in late June that year when the Polish and Israeli prime ministers issued a joint communiqu\u00e9 endorsing research into the Jewish Holocaust and condemning the expression, \"Polish concentration camps\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/06/27/world/europe/ap-eu-poland-holocaust-law-the-latest.html|title=The Latest: Party Head: Israel Confirms Polish View on Nazis|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en}}</ref>\n \nIn March 2018 a new Polish law took effect, banning nearly all commerce on Sundays, with supermarkets and most other retailers closed Sundays for the first time since liberal shopping laws were introduced in the 1990s. The law had been passed by the [[Law and Justice]] party with Morawiecki's support.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2018-03-11/most-stores-shut-in-poland-as-sunday-trade-ban-takes-effect</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4076186/poland-sunday-shopping-ban/|title=Stores shut across Poland as Sunday shopping ban takes effect|website=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2018/0311/946597-poland-shopping/|title=Sunday trading ban comes into effect in Poland|date=March 11, 2018|via=www.rte.ie}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/2/Artykul/353341,Stores-closed-as-Poland-phases-out-Sunday-shopping|title=Stores closed as Poland phases out Sunday shopping|website=Polskie Radio dla Zagranicy}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wizyta w Watykanie (40747742770).jpg|thumb|Morawiecki with [[Pope Francis]], [[Vatican City]], June 2018]]\n\nAs other [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] leaders, Morawiecki opposes any [[European migrant crisis#Reactions|compulsory EU long-term quota]] on redistribution of migrants. In May 2018, Morawiecki said: \"Proposals by the European Union that impose quotas on us hit the very foundations of national sovereignty.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Refugee quotas \u2018hit foundations of national sovereignty\u2019: Polish PM |url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/10/Artykul/363401,Refugee-quotas-%E2%80%98hit-foundations-of-national-sovereignty%E2%80%99-Polish-PM |work=Radio Poland |date=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018 Morawiecki said he \"will not rest\" until \"the whole truth\" of the [[World War II]]-era [[massacres of Poles in Volhynia and Eastern Galicia|massacres in Volhynia and Eastern Galicia]] have been explained. Between 1942 and 1945, members of the [[Ukrainian Insurgent Army]] (UPA) killed up to 100,000 civilians in nowadays Western Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Polish PM pledges to fight for 'whole truth' of WWII massacres |url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/372575,Polish-PM-pledges-to-fight-for-whole-truth-of-brutal-WWII-massacres |work=Radio Poland |date=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ukrainian nationalists plan protests against Polish anti-defamation law |url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/10/Artykul/347692,Ukrainian-nationalists-plan-protests-against-Polish-antidefamation-law |work=Radio Poland |date=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn the issue of [[Brexit]], Morawiecki told the BBC in January 2019 that more and more Polish people are returning to Poland from the UK and he hoped the trend would continue to help boost the Polish economy. He urged the UK, 'give us our people back'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/mateusz-morawiecki-poland-uk-give-us-our-people-back-brexit/|title=Polish PM to UK: \u2018Give us our people back\u2019|first=Ian|last=Geoghegan|date=January 24, 2019|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019 Morawiecki implied that [[Nazism]] was not responsible for the [[Holocaust]] and other atrocities committed by the Nazi government between 1933 and 1945, claiming that \"[[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]]'s [[Germany]] fed on fascist ideology... But all the evil came from this (German) state and we cannot forget that, because otherwise we relativise evil.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Polish PM says Hitler's Germany responsible for Holocaust, not Nazis |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190127-polish-pm-says-hitlers-germany-responsible-holocaust-not-nazis |work=France 24 |date=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other posts==\n* Ex-officio member, Board of Governors, [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] (AIIB)<ref>[https://www.aiib.org/en/about-aiib/governance/board-governors/index.html Board of Governors] [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] (AIIB).</ref>\n* Ex-officio member, Board of Governors, [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF)<ref>[http://www.imf.org/external/np/sec/memdir/members.aspx Board of Governors] [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF).</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2008 Morawiecki was made [[Honorary Consul]] of the [[Republic of Ireland]] in [[Poland]]. In 2013 he was awarded the [[Cross of Freedom and Solidarity]]. In 2015, he became the recipient of the Knight's Cross of the [[Order of Polonia Restituta]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2019, he was awarded the title ''Man of the Year'' at the annual [[Economic Forum in Krynica|Krynica Economic Forum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.money.pl/gospodarka/forum-ekonomiczne-w-krynicy-zdroju-mateusz-morawiecki-z-nagroda-czlowieka-roku-6420879879170177a.html |title=Forum Ekonomiczne w Krynicy-Zdroju. Mateusz Morawiecki z nagrod\u0105 Cz\u0142owieka Roku |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> He has also received other distinctions from economic clubs, universities, publishing houses, and cultural institutions.\n\n==Personal life==\nMorawiecki is married to Iwona Morawiecka, with whom he has four children: two daughters (Olga and Magdalena) and two sons (Jeremiasz and Ignacy).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wroclaw.wyborcza.pl/wroclaw/1,142076,19176075,mateusz-morawiecki-z-wyzyn-bankowosci-do-rzadu-pis-ku-chwale.html?disableRedirects=true|title=Wyborcza.pl|website=wroclaw.wyborcza.pl}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fakt.pl/wydarzenia/polityka/rodzina-zona-i-dzieci-mateusza-morawieckiego/jvlptr4 |title=Oto rodzina Morawieckiego. Uchylamy r\u0105bka tajemnicy! |access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref>\n\nTwo of his [[aunts]] married [[History of the Jews in Poland|Jewish]] men and [[conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]]. One aunt was saved during the [[Jewish Holocaust]] by a [[Righteous among the Nations]].<ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/poland-appoints-ex-banker-with-jewish-roots-as-prime-minister Poland appoints ex-banker with Jewish roots as prime minister] By JTA, 8 December 2017</ref>\n\n==State-visits gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Mateusz Morawiecki i Theresa May.JPG|Morawiecki with [[Theresa May]], [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]] 2017\nImage:Emmanuel Macron i Mateusz Morawiecki.JPG|Morawiecki with [[Emmanuel Macron]], Brussels 2017\nImage:Premier Mateusz Morawiecki na szczycie premier\u00f3w Grupy Wyszehradzkiej (26036436518).jpg|Morawiecki with [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] leaders, [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]] 2018\nImage:Petro Poroszenko i Mateusz Morawiecki.JPG|Morawiecki with [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] president [[Petro Poroshenko]], [[Munich]], [[Germany]] 2018\nImage:Mulatu Teshome with Mateusz Morawiecki in Warsaw - 2018 (40792938585).jpg|Morawiecki with [[Mulatu Teshome]], [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] 2018\nImage:Premier Mateusz Morawiecki i pani premier Rumunii Viorica D\u0103ncil\u0103.jpg|Morawiecki with [[Viorica D\u0103ncil\u0103]], [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] 2018\nImage:Spotkanie z wiceprezydentem Stan\u00f3w Zjednoczonych.jpg|Morawiecki with [[Mike Pence]], [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] 2019\nImage:Gitanas Nauseda and Mateusz Morawiecki official meeting in 2019.jpg|Morawiecki with [[Gitanas Naus\u0117da]], [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]], 2019\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120830092105/http://www.bzwbk.pl/english/management-board/management-board.html Bank Zachodni WBK Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Poland]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Janusz Piechoci\u0144ski]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Deputy Prime Minister of Poland]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Maria Wasiak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Minister of Development]]|years=2015\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Jerzy Kwieci\u0144ski]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pawe\u0142 Sza\u0142amacha]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Minister of Finance]]|years=2016\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Teresa Czerwi\u0144ska]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Witold Ba\u0144ka]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Sport and Tourism (Poland)|Minister of Sports and Tourism]]|years=2019\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Danuta Dmowska]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Poland}}\n{{Finance Ministers of Poland}}\n{{PolishSportMinisters}}\n{{European Council}}\n{{Current NATO leaders}}\n{{Beata Szyd\u0142o Cabinet}}\n{{Mateusz Morawiecki Cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morawiecki, Mateusz}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Finance Ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of Polonia Restituta]]\n[[Category:Law and Justice politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Polish Sejm 2019\u20132023]]\n[[Category:Polish economists]]\n[[Category:Polish historians]]\n[[Category:Polish publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Polish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Wroc\u0142aw]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Poland]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Cross of Freedom and Solidarity]]\n[[Category:University of Basel alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Wroc\u0142aw alumni]]\n[[Category:Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics alumni]]\n[[Category:Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|17th Prime Minister of Poland}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Mateusz Morawiecki\n| image = Mateusz Morawiecki Prezes Rady Ministr\u00f3w (cropped).jpg\n| office = 17th [[Prime Minister of Poland]]\n| president = [[Andrzej Duda]]\n| deputy = [[Piotr Gli\u0144ski]]<br>[[Jaros\u0142aw Gowin]]<br>[[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]<br>[[Jacek Sasin]]\n| term_start = 11 December 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Deputy Prime Minister of Poland]]\n| 1blankname1 = Served with\n| 1namedata1 = {{Ublist|[[Piotr Gli\u0144ski]]<br/>[[Jaros\u0142aw Gowin]]}}\n| primeminister1 = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| term_start1 = 16 November 2015\n| term_end1 = 11 December 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Janusz Piechoci\u0144ski]]\n| successor1 = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| office2 = [[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Minister of Finance]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| term_start2 = 28 September 2016\n| term_end2 = 9 January 2018\n| predecessor2 = [[Pawe\u0142 Sza\u0142amacha]]\n| successor2 = [[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Teresa Czerwi\u0144ska]]\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Minister of Development]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]\n| term_start3 = 16 November 2015\n| term_end3 = 9 January 2018\n| predecessor3 = [[Maria Wasiak]]\n| successor3 = [[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Jerzy Kwieci\u0144ski]]\n| birth_name = Mateusz Jakub Morawiecki\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|06|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Wroc\u0142aw]], [[Polish People\u2019s Republic|Poland]]\n| death_place = \n| party = [[Law and Justice]] (2016\u2013present)<br>[[Independent politician|Independent]] (before 2016)\n| spouse = Iwona Morawiecka\n| occupation = Economist, historian, magazine editor, politician\n| children = 4\n| relatives = [[Kornel Morawiecki]] {{small|(Father)}}\n| education = [[University of Wroc\u0142aw]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Wroc\u0142aw University of Science and Technology]]<br>[[Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics]] {{small|([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])}}<br>[[University of Hamburg]]<br>[[University of Basel]] {{small|([[Master of Advanced Studies|MAS]])}}\n| signature = Mateusz Morawiecki's signature 2017.jpg\n| website = www.premier.gov.pl\n}}\n\n'''Mateusz Jakub Morawiecki''' ({{small|Polish pronunciation:}} {{IPAc-pl|m|\u0254|r|a|v|i|\u02c8|\u025b|ts|k|\u02b2|i}}; born 20 June 1968) is a [[Poles|Polish]] [[economist]], [[historian]], and [[politician]] who has been the [[Prime Minister of Poland]] since December 2017. He previously served in the [[Cabinet of Beata Szyd\u0142o|Cabinet]] of Prime Minister [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]] as [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Deputy Prime Minister]] from 2015 to 2017, [[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Minister of Finance]] from 2016 to 2018, and [[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Minister of Development]] between 2015 and 2018. Prior to his political appointment, Morawiecki had an extensive business career. \n\nBorn in [[Wroc\u0142aw]], Morawiecki became heavily engaged in anti-communist movements in his youth. He attended the [[University of Wroc\u0142aw]] and extended his education at the [[University of Hamburg|Universities of Hamburg]] and [[University of Basel|Basel]]. He obtained degrees in arts, business administration, and advanced studies. From 1996 to 2004, Morawiecki lectured at the [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics]], as well as from 1996 to 1998 at the [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology]]. From November 1998, Morawiecki worked for [[Bank Zachodni WBK]] from the [[Banco Santander|Santander Group]], where he was promoted to the position of managing director and eventually chairman.\n\nOn 11 December 2017, Morawiecki was nominated as Prime Minister of Poland (''premier'') by the chief staff of the ruling [[Law and Justice]] party.\n\n==Early life and education ==\nMateusz Morawiecki was born 20 June 1968 in [[Wroc\u0142aw]], southwest Poland, to [[Kornel Morawiecki]], physicist and [[Fighting Solidarity]] leader, and his wife Jadwiga. Morawiecki is of distant [[Germans|German]] descent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wprost.pl/tygodnik/10103523/rodzinna-lustracja-premiera.html|title=Rodzinna lustracja premiera|date=February 11, 2018|website=Wprost}}</ref> The [[Times of Israel]] also reported in 2017 that Morawiecki has \"Jewish roots\", however this claim has not been confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/poland-appoints-ex-banker-with-jewish-roots-as-prime-minister/|title=Poland appoints ex-banker with Jewish roots as prime minister|author=JTA|newspaper=Times of Israel|date=8 December 2017|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt age 12<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazetaprawna.pl/artykuly/1090531,kim-jest-mateusz-morawiecki.html|title=Kim jest kandydat na premiera Mateusz Morawiecki [SYLWETKA]|website=www.gazetaprawna.pl}}</ref> Morawiecki was already active in the Polish [[anti-communism|anti-communist]] movement, duplicating illegal political leaflets. In August 1980 he posted a poster edition of the ''Lower Silesia Bulletin'' all over [[Wroc\u0142aw]]. The poster listed the [[Gda\u0144sk Agreement#List of Points|Gda\u0144sk Demands]] and, in their support, called for a general strike on Poland's [[Baltic Sea]] coast. After [[Martial law in Poland|martial law]] was declared in 1981, he printed and distributed underground [[Solidarity (Polish trade union)|Solidarity]] magazines.\n\nHe publicly confessed to terrorist activities in the 1980s. Together with a group of friends, he was supposed to throw Molotov cocktails at police cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wprost.pl/polityka/10297541/morawiecki-o-czasach-prl-rzucalem-koktajlami-molotowa-do-tej-pory-koledzy-wspominaja-moje-poranione-plecy.html|title=Morawiecki o czasach PRL: Rzuca\u0142em koktajlami Mo\u0142otowa (...) do tej pory koledzy wspominaj\u0105 moje poranione plecy|last=WPROST.pl|date=2020-02-11|website=Wprost|language=pl|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nDespite repeated arrests and beatings by Poland's Security Service (''[[S\u0142u\u017cba Bezpiecze\u0144stwa]]'', ''SB''), until the late 1980s he continued taking part in political demonstrations. He edited the ''Lower Silesia Bulletin'' and was active in the Independent Students' Association. In 1988 and 1989 he participated in occupation strikes at the University of Wroclaw. He co-organized the Club for Political Thought, \"Free and Solidary\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://kobieta.onet.pl/w-domu-nigdy-o-tym-nie-opowiadal-nie-chcial-martwic-matki-dziecinstwo-premiera/bt99r3q |title=\"W domu nigdy o tym nie opowiada\u0142. Nie chcia\u0142 martwi\u0107 matki\". Dzieci\u0144stwo premiera wspomina jego mama |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMorawiecki is an alumnus of the [[University of Wroc\u0142aw]] (history, 1992), [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology]] (1993), [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics]] ([[Business Administration]], 1995), the [[University of Hamburg]] (European Law and Economic Integration, 1995\u201397), and the [[University of Basel]] ([[European Studies]], 1995\u201397). While at the Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology, he studied abroad at [[Central Connecticut State University]] and completed an advanced executive program at [[Northwestern University]]'s [[Kellogg School of Management]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://oko.press/ludzie/morawiecki-mateusz/ |title=Mateusz Morawiecki |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premier.gov.pl/ludzie/mateusz-morawiecki.html |title=Mateusz Morawiecki |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nIn 1991 Morawiecki began work at Cogito Company and co-created two publishing firms, Reverentia and Enter Marketing-Publishing. That same year he co-founded the magazine ''Dwa Dni'' (Two Days), later becoming editor-in-chief. \n\nIn 1995 he completed an [[internship]] at [[Deutsche Bundesbank]] in credit analysis, financial restructuring, banking supervision, and financial market supervision. In 1996\u201397 he conducted banking and macroeconomic research at the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|University of Frankfurt]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://bruegel.org/author/mateusz-morawiecki/ |title=Mateusz Morawiecki |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> In 1998, as deputy director of the Accession Negotiations Department in the Committee for European Integration, he oversaw and participated in numerous areas, including finance, of the negotiations for [[Poland in the European Union|Polish accession to the European Union]]. \n\nWith Frank Emmert, he co-authored the first textbook on ''The Law of the European Union'' published in Poland.\n\nFrom 1996 to 2004 Morawiecki lectured at the [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Economics]], and from 1996 to 1998 also at the [[Wroc\u0142aw University of Technology]]. He sat on policy committees at many institutions of higher education. From 1998 to 2001 he was a member of the supervisory boards of the Wa\u0142brzych Power Company, Dialog (a local telephone-service provider), and the Industrial Development Agency. From 1998 to 2002 he was a member of the [[Lower Silesian Regional Assembly]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.umwd.dolnyslask.pl/sejmik/radni-wojewodztwa/radni-i-kadencji/ |title=I Kadencja Sejmiku Wojew\u00f3dztwa Dolno\u015bl\u0105skiego |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom November 1998 Morawiecki worked for [[Bank Zachodni WBK]], [[Banco Santander|Santander Group]], where he began his career as deputy chair of the supervisory board, and supervisor of the economic analysis bureau and the international trade department. In 2001 he became managing director and a member of the board. In 2007\u201315 Morawiecki was chairman of [[Bank Zachodni WBK]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wprost.pl/tematy/10126719/mateusz-morawiecki.html |title=Mateusz Morawiecki |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Mateusz Morawiecki na otwarciu Campus Warsaw.jpg|thumb|left|upright 1.0|Morawiecki at opening of Campus Warsaw]]\nOn 16 November 2015, President [[Andrzej Duda]] appointed Mateusz Morawiecki as both [[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Deputy Prime Minister]] and [[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Minister of Development]] in the Cabinet led by Prime Minister [[Beata Szyd\u0142o]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116143425/http://www.prezydent.pl/aktualnosci/nominacje/art,3,prezydent-powolal-rzad.html|title=Oficjalna strona Prezydenta Rzeczypospolitej Polskiej / Aktualno\u015bci / Nominacje / Prezydent powo\u0142a\u0142 rz\u0105d|date=2015-11-16|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref> (This took place soon after Mateusz Morawiecki's father, [[Kornel Morawiecki]], was elected to Poland's lower chamber of the parliament<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sejm.gov.pl/Sejm8.nsf/posel.xsp?id=255&type=A|title=Kornel Morawiecki|website=sejm.gov.pl|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref> and the [[Law and Justice]] party won the [[2015 Polish parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary elections]].)\n\nIn March 2016, Mateusz Morawiecki announced that he had joined the Law and Justice party.\n\nOn 28 September 2016, in addition to his other positions, Morawiecki was appointed [[Minister of Finance (Poland)|Minister of Finance]], becoming the second most powerful member of the Government, overseeing the budget, government finances, [[European Union]] funds, and overall economic policy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/polish-reshuffle-puts-sights-on-prime-minister/ |title=Polish reshuffle puts sights on prime minister |publisher=POLITICO |date=29 September 2016 |accessdate=21 October 2016 |language=en }}</ref>\n\nAs Finance Minister, Morawiecki outlined an ambitious \"Plan for Responsible Development\", known colloquially as the \"Morawiecki Plan\", aimed at stimulating economic growth and raising revenues for generous government plans, including \u201cFamily 500+\u201d child benefits for all families with two or more children.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/12/Artykul/273305,Trillions-needed-to-modernise-Poland-deputy-minister|title=Trillions needed to modernise Poland: deputy minister|publisher=Radio Poland |date=30 September 2016 |accessdate=21 October 2016 |language=en }}</ref> In March 2017, he took part in a meeting of [[G20]] finance ministers in [[Baden-Baden]], becoming Poland's first-ever representative at that summit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rp.pl/Gospodarka/303169812-Morawiecki-wsrod-ministrow-finansow-G20.html#ap-1|title=Morawiecki w\u015br\u00f3d ministr\u00f3w finans\u00f3w G20 - Gospodarka - rp.pl|access-date=2017-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tvn24bis.pl/ze-swiata,75/rzeczy-ktore-musisz-wiedziec-o-szczycie-g20,724315.html|title=Rzeczy, kt\u00f3re musisz wiedzie\u0107 o szczycie G20 {{!}} Ze \u015bwiata|work=TVN24 BiS|access-date=2017-03-31|language=pl}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Poland==\n[[File:Premier Mateusz Morawiecki na spotkaniach Grupy Wyszehradzkiej przed szczytem Rady Europejskiej (38167092585).jpg|thumb|Morawiecki with [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] (V4) leaders and [[President of the European Commission|European Commission President]] [[Jean Claude Juncker]], Brussels 2017]]\n\nIn December 2017, [[Jaros\u0142aw Kaczy\u0144ski]], the Chairman of the Law and Justice party, declared that he no longer had confidence in Beata Szyd\u0142o to be the party's prime ministerial candidate, in part due to perceived conflict between her and other European Union leaders. With her position untenable, Szyd\u0142o resigned, and Morawiecki quickly won internal party approval to be nominated as her successor. He was sworn in as [[Prime Minister of Poland]] on 11 December, immediately appointing Szyd\u0142o as his deputy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Komitet Polityczny PiS desygnowa\u0142 Mateusza Morawieckiego na Premiera|url=http://pis.org.pl/aktualnosci/komitet-polityczny-pis-desygnowal-mateusza-morawieckiego-na-premiera|website=Prawo i Sprawiedliwo\u015b\u0107|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref> In his first major address to [[Sejm]], he pledged \u201ccontinuity\u201d rather than radical change.<ref>Micha\u0142 Broniatowski (December 12, 2017), [https://www.politico.eu/article/poland-new-prime-minister-mateusz-morawiecki-wont-change-anything-after-leadership-swap/ Poland\u2019s new PM won\u2019t change anything after leadership swap] ''[[Politico Europe]]''.</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, following a highly public [[racist]] incident in [[Warsaw]], Morawiecki declared: \"There is no place in Poland for racism. The attack on a girl because of her skin color deserves the strongest condemnation. We shall do everything to make Poland safe for everyone.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=No place for racism in Poland, says PM after attack on teen|url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/342885,No-place-for-racism-in-Poland-says-PM-after-attack-on-teen|website=Radio Poland|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, both chambers of the Polish parliament (the [[Sejm]] and [[Senate of Poland|Senate]]) adopted an [[Amendment to the Act on the Institute of National Remembrance]] criminalising the ascription to Poles collectively of complicity in [[World War II]] [[Holocaust|Jewish-genocide]]-related or other [[war crime]]s or [[crimes against humanity]] that had been committed by the [[Axis powers]], and condemning use of the expression, [[\"Polish death camp\" controversy|\"Polish death camp\"]].<ref name=\"wapo20180127\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/01/27/it-could-soon-be-a-crime-to-blame-poland-for-nazi-atrocities-and-israel-is-appalled/  Israel and Poland try to tamp down tensions after Poland\u2019s \u2018death camp\u2019 law sparks Israeli outrage], Washington Post, 28 January 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-israel-poland/israel-and-poland-clash-over-proposed-holocaust-law-idUSKBN1FH0S3 Israel and Poland clash over proposed Holocaust law], Reuters, 28 January 2018</ref><ref name=\"SmithsonianJan2018\">[https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/poland-grants-initial-approval-controversial-death-camp-bill-180967975/ The Controversy Around Poland\u2019s Proposed Ban on the Term \u201cPolish Death Camps\u201d], Smithsonian.com, 29 January 2018</ref> The law sparked a crisis in [[Israel\u2013Poland relations]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/latest-poland-reverses-disputed-holocaust-law-56194754|title=The Latest: Party head: Israel confirms Polish view on Nazis|last=News|first=ABC|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en}}</ref>  \n\n[[File:Angela Merkel i Mateusz Morawiecki.JPG|thumb|left|Morawiecki with [[Angela Merkel]], [[Berlin]], February 2018]]\n\nAt the Munich Security Conference on 17 February that year, Morawiecki said \"it is not going to be seen as criminal to say that there were Polish perpetrators, as there were [[Jews|Jewish]] perpetrators, as there were [[Russians|Russian]] perpetrators, as there were [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] perpetrators, not only [[Germans|German]] perpetrators.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/poland-mateusz-morawiecki-israel-netanyahu-holocaust-jewish-perpetrators/|title=\"Jewish perpetrators\" remark reignites Poland Holocaust dispute|date=19 February 2018|work=CBS News}}</ref><ref name=\"jpost\">{{cite news |title=Polish MP: I hope my prime minister is being stupid and not ruthless |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Polish-MP-I-hope-my-prime-minister-is-being-stupid-and-not-ruthless-542986 |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=19 February 2018}}</ref> His remark roused controversy and prompted criticism by prominent Israeli politicians, including [[Israel|Israeli]] Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/poland-mateusz-morawiecki-israel-netanyahu-holocaust-jewish-perpetrators/|title=\"Jewish perpetrators\" remark reignites Poland Holocaust dispute|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/benjamin-netanyahu-mateusz-morawiecki-jews-perpetrators-holocaust-munich-security-conference-a8216421.html Benjamin Netanyahu attacks Polish PM for saying Jews were among perpetrators of the Holocaust]\". ''The Independent.'' 18 February 2018.</ref> and Israeli President [[Reuven Rivlin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/polish-embassy-in-israel-vandalized-after-polish-pm-controversial-remarks/4260010.html|title=Polish Embassy in Israel Vandalized After Polish PM's Controversial Remarks|date=18 February 2018|work=VOA News}}</ref> The crisis was resolved in late June that year when the Polish and Israeli prime ministers issued a joint communiqu\u00e9 endorsing research into the Jewish Holocaust and condemning the expression, \"Polish concentration camps\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/06/27/world/europe/ap-eu-poland-holocaust-law-the-latest.html|title=The Latest: Party Head: Israel Confirms Polish View on Nazis|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en}}</ref>\n \nIn March 2018 a new Polish law took effect, banning nearly all commerce on Sundays, with supermarkets and most other retailers closed Sundays for the first time since liberal shopping laws were introduced in the 1990s. The law had been passed by the [[Law and Justice]] party with Morawiecki's support.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/business/articles/2018-03-11/most-stores-shut-in-poland-as-sunday-trade-ban-takes-effect</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4076186/poland-sunday-shopping-ban/|title=Stores shut across Poland as Sunday shopping ban takes effect|website=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2018/0311/946597-poland-shopping/|title=Sunday trading ban comes into effect in Poland|date=March 11, 2018|via=www.rte.ie}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/2/Artykul/353341,Stores-closed-as-Poland-phases-out-Sunday-shopping|title=Stores closed as Poland phases out Sunday shopping|website=Polskie Radio dla Zagranicy}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wizyta w Watykanie (40747742770).jpg|thumb|Morawiecki with [[Pope Francis]], [[Vatican City]], June 2018]]\n\nAs other [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] leaders, Morawiecki opposes any [[European migrant crisis#Reactions|compulsory EU long-term quota]] on redistribution of migrants. In May 2018, Morawiecki said: \"Proposals by the European Union that impose quotas on us hit the very foundations of national sovereignty.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Refugee quotas \u2018hit foundations of national sovereignty\u2019: Polish PM |url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/10/Artykul/363401,Refugee-quotas-%E2%80%98hit-foundations-of-national-sovereignty%E2%80%99-Polish-PM |work=Radio Poland |date=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018 Morawiecki said he \"will not rest\" until \"the whole truth\" of the [[World War II]]-era [[massacres of Poles in Volhynia and Eastern Galicia|massacres in Volhynia and Eastern Galicia]] have been explained. Between 1942 and 1945, members of the [[Ukrainian Insurgent Army]] (UPA) killed up to 100,000 civilians in nowadays Western Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Polish PM pledges to fight for 'whole truth' of WWII massacres |url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/372575,Polish-PM-pledges-to-fight-for-whole-truth-of-brutal-WWII-massacres |work=Radio Poland |date=11 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ukrainian nationalists plan protests against Polish anti-defamation law |url=http://www.thenews.pl/1/10/Artykul/347692,Ukrainian-nationalists-plan-protests-against-Polish-antidefamation-law |work=Radio Poland |date=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn the issue of [[Brexit]], Morawiecki told the BBC in January 2019 that more and more Polish people are returning to Poland from the UK and he hoped the trend would continue to help boost the Polish economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/mateusz-morawiecki-poland-uk-give-us-our-people-back-brexit/|title=Polish PM to UK: \u2018Give us our people back\u2019|first=Ian|last=Geoghegan|date=January 24, 2019|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019 Morawiecki said that \"[[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]]'s [[Germany]] fed on fascist ideology... But all the evil came from this (German) state and we cannot forget that, because otherwise we relativise evil.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Polish PM says Hitler's Germany responsible for Holocaust, not Nazis |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190127-polish-pm-says-hitlers-germany-responsible-holocaust-not-nazis |work=France 24 |date=27 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Other posts==\n* Ex-officio member, Board of Governors, [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] (AIIB)<ref>[https://www.aiib.org/en/about-aiib/governance/board-governors/index.html Board of Governors] [[Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank]] (AIIB).</ref>\n* Ex-officio member, Board of Governors, [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF)<ref>[http://www.imf.org/external/np/sec/memdir/members.aspx Board of Governors] [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF).</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2008 Morawiecki was made [[Honorary Consul]] of the [[Republic of Ireland]] in [[Poland]]. In 2013 he was awarded the [[Cross of Freedom and Solidarity]]. In 2015, he became the recipient of the Knight's Cross of the [[Order of Polonia Restituta]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2019, he was awarded the title ''Man of the Year'' at the annual [[Economic Forum in Krynica|Krynica Economic Forum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.money.pl/gospodarka/forum-ekonomiczne-w-krynicy-zdroju-mateusz-morawiecki-z-nagroda-czlowieka-roku-6420879879170177a.html |title=Forum Ekonomiczne w Krynicy-Zdroju. Mateusz Morawiecki z nagrod\u0105 Cz\u0142owieka Roku |access-date=5 October 2019}}</ref> He has also received other distinctions from economic clubs, universities, publishing houses, and cultural institutions.\n\n==Personal life==\nMorawiecki is married to Iwona Morawiecka, with whom he has four children: two daughters (Olga and Magdalena) and two sons (Jeremiasz and Ignacy).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wroclaw.wyborcza.pl/wroclaw/1,142076,19176075,mateusz-morawiecki-z-wyzyn-bankowosci-do-rzadu-pis-ku-chwale.html?disableRedirects=true|title=Wyborcza.pl|website=wroclaw.wyborcza.pl}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fakt.pl/wydarzenia/polityka/rodzina-zona-i-dzieci-mateusza-morawieckiego/jvlptr4 |title=Oto rodzina Morawieckiego. Uchylamy r\u0105bka tajemnicy! |access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref>\n\nTwo of his [[aunts]] married [[History of the Jews in Poland|Jewish]] men and [[conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]]. One aunt was saved during the [[Jewish Holocaust]] by a [[Righteous among the Nations]].<ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/poland-appoints-ex-banker-with-jewish-roots-as-prime-minister Poland appoints ex-banker with Jewish roots as prime minister] By JTA, 8 December 2017</ref>\n\n==State-visits gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Mateusz Morawiecki i Theresa May.JPG|Morawiecki with [[Theresa May]], [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]] 2017\nImage:Emmanuel Macron i Mateusz Morawiecki.JPG|Morawiecki with [[Emmanuel Macron]], Brussels 2017\nImage:Premier Mateusz Morawiecki na szczycie premier\u00f3w Grupy Wyszehradzkiej (26036436518).jpg|Morawiecki with [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] leaders, [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]] 2018\nImage:Petro Poroszenko i Mateusz Morawiecki.JPG|Morawiecki with [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] president [[Petro Poroshenko]], [[Munich]], [[Germany]] 2018\nImage:Mulatu Teshome with Mateusz Morawiecki in Warsaw - 2018 (40792938585).jpg|Morawiecki with [[Mulatu Teshome]], [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] 2018\nImage:Premier Mateusz Morawiecki i pani premier Rumunii Viorica D\u0103ncil\u0103.jpg|Morawiecki with [[Viorica D\u0103ncil\u0103]], [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] 2018\nImage:Spotkanie z wiceprezydentem Stan\u00f3w Zjednoczonych.jpg|Morawiecki with [[Mike Pence]], [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]] 2019\nImage:Gitanas Nauseda and Mateusz Morawiecki official meeting in 2019.jpg|Morawiecki with [[Gitanas Naus\u0117da]], [[Warsaw]], [[Poland]], 2019\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120830092105/http://www.bzwbk.pl/english/management-board/management-board.html Bank Zachodni WBK Profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Poland]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Janusz Piechoci\u0144ski]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Deputy Prime Minister of the Republic of Poland|Deputy Prime Minister of Poland]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beata Szyd\u0142o]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Maria Wasiak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Minister of Development]]|years=2015\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ministry of Development (Poland)|Jerzy Kwieci\u0144ski]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Pawe\u0142 Sza\u0142amacha]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Minister of Finance]]|years=2016\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ministry of Finance (Poland)|Teresa Czerwi\u0144ska]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Witold Ba\u0144ka]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Sport and Tourism (Poland)|Minister of Sports and Tourism]]|years=2019\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Danuta Dmowska]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Poland}}\n{{Finance Ministers of 