{"title_page": "Shorea acuminatissima", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|status = CR\n|status_system = IUCN2.3\n|image = CO 1069-537-11 (7929825882).jpg\n|genus = Shorea\n|species = acuminatissima\n|authority = Sym.\n}}\n\n'''''Shorea acuminatissima''''' (called, along with some other species in the genus ''[[Shorea]]'', '''yellow meranti''') is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Dipterocarpaceae]]. It is [[endemism|endemic]] to [[Borneo]]. It is threatened by [[habitat loss]].\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite journal | author = Ashton, P. | title = ''Shorea acuminatissima'' | journal = [[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume = 1998 | page = e.T33402A9780268 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | date = 1998 | url = http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/33402/0 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.1998.RLTS.T33402A9780268.en | access-date = 22 December 2017}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5490408}}\n\n[[Category:Shorea|acuminatissima]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Borneo]]\n[[Category:Trees of Borneo]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered flora of Asia]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Dipterocarpaceae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|status = CR\n|status_system = IUCN2.3\n|image = CO 1069-537-11 (7929825882).jpg\n|genus = Shorea\n|species = acuminatissima\n|authority = Sym.\n}}\n\n'''''Shorea acuminatissima''''' (called, along with some other species in the genus ''[[Shorea]]'', '''Yellow Meranti''') is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Dipterocarpaceae]]. It is [[endemism|endemic]] to [[Borneo]]. It is threatened by [[habitat loss]].\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite journal | author = Ashton, P. | title = ''Shorea acuminatissima'' | journal = [[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume = 1998 | page = e.T33402A9780268 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | date = 1998 | url = http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/33402/0 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.1998.RLTS.T33402A9780268.en | access-date = 22 December 2017}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5490408}}\n\n[[Category:Shorea|acuminatissima]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Borneo]]\n[[Category:Trees of Borneo]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered flora of Asia]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Dipterocarpaceae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shorea_acuminatissima"}
{"title_page": "The Man Who Sold the World", "text_new": "{{short description|1970 single by David Bowie}}\n{{about|the song|the album|The Man Who Sold the World (album)}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = The Man Who Sold the World\n| cover    = File:Spaceoddity.png\n| caption  = 1973 US picture sleeve\n| alt      =\n| type     = Single\n| artist   = [[David Bowie]]\n| album    = [[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]\n| A-side   = {{Unbulleted list|\"[[Life on Mars (song)|Life on Mars?]]\" (UK)|\"[[Space Oddity]]\" (US)}}\n| released = \n*{{Start date|1970|11|04|df=y}} (US)\n*April 1971 (UK)<br>22 June 1973 (US and UK reissue)\n| recorded = 4 & 22 May 1970 \n| studio   = [[Trident Studios|Trident]] & [[Advision Studios|Advision]], London\n| genre    = [[Hard rock]]\n| length   = {{Duration|m=3|s=55}}\n| label    = [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]<br>[[RCA Records|RCA]] (1973 reissue)\n| writer   = David Bowie\n| producer = [[Tony Visconti]]\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = File:David-bowie-the-man-who-sold-the-world-rca-s.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Picture sleeve for the 1983 UK reissue\n}}\n}}\n\"'''The Man Who Sold the World'''\" is a song written and performed by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]]. The title track of Bowie's [[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|third album]], it was released in November 1970 in the US and in April 1971 in the UK. The song has been covered by a number of other artists, notably by [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]], who had a UK No. 3 hit with her version in 1974; by [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], whose 1993 performance of the song for the television program ''[[MTV Unplugged]]'' introduced it to a new audience; and by [[Midge Ure]], whose 1982 cover of the song was featured in the 2015 video game ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain]]'' because the game itself features the song's main theme of doppelg\u00e4ngers.\n\nThe song was reworked by Bowie, featuring atmospheric synths, a new bassline, techno-style drums and a notably darker mood, for performances in concerts from 1995 to 1997, including the [[1995 MTV Europe Music Awards]]. Bowie later returned to playing the original version in the 2000s.\n\n==Recording==\nThe backing track for \"The Man Who Sold the World\" was recorded at [[Trident Studios]] in London on 4 May 1970, along with other album track \"Running Gun Blues\". At this point, the track was recorded under the working title \"Saviour Machine\" and did not contain the title phrase.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=191\u2013192}} According to producer [[Tony Visconti]], Bowie recorded his vocal on 22 May at [[Advision Studios]], the final day of mixing for the album which, when traveling to Advision, Bowie had intended to name ''Metrobolist'', an homage to [[Fritz Lang]]'s 1927 film ''[[Metropolis (1927 film)|Metropolis]]''.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=193}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=316}} Bowie's last-minute addition frustrated Visconti, who recalled in 1977: \"This was the beginning of [Bowie's] new style of writing \u2013 'I can't be bothered until I have to'. When it was finished, on the last day of the last mix, I remember telling David, 'I've had it, I can't work like this anymore \u2013 I'm through...David was very disappointed.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=193\u2013194}} This frustration was mostly due in part to his dissatisfaction with the recording sessions: he was mostly in charge of budget and production, as well as maintaining Bowie's interest in the project. Bowie later told [[BBC Radio 1]]'s Stuart Grundy in 1976: \"It was a nightmare, that album. I hated the actual process of making it.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=210}}\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe person in the song has an encounter with a kind of [[doppelg\u00e4nger]], as suggested in the second chorus where \"I never lost control\" is replaced with \"We never lost control\".<ref>{{Cite book| contribution = Future Legends: David Bowie and Science Fiction| last = King| first = Maureen| editor-last = Morrison| editor-first = Michael A.| title = Trajectories of the Fantastic: Selected Essays from the Fourteenth International Conference on the Fantastic in the Arts| publisher = Greenwood| year = 1997| location = Westport, CT| page = 131 }}</ref> Beyond this, the episode is unexplained: as James E. Perone wrote,\n\n{{quote|Bowie encounters the title character, but it is not clear just what the phrase means, or exactly who this man is.&nbsp;... The main thing that the song does is to paint \u2013 however elusively \u2013 the title character as another example of the societal outcasts who populate the album.<ref>{{Cite book| last = Perone| first = James E.| title = The Words and Music of David Bowie| publisher = Praeger| year = 2007| location = Westport, Connecticut| pages = 15\u201316}}</ref>}}\n\nIn common with a number of tracks on the album, the song's themes have been compared to the [[Horror fiction|horror]]-[[fantasy]] works of [[H. P. Lovecraft]].{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=38}} The lyrics are also cited as reflecting Bowie's concerns with splintered or multiple personalities, and are believed to have been partially inspired by the poem \"[[Antigonish (poem)|Antigonish]]\" by [[William Hughes Mearns]]:{{sfn|Buckley|1999|p=100}}<ref name=\"Thompson AllMusic\">{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Dave |title=\"The Man Who Sold the World\" \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/the-man-who-sold-the-world-mt0052219335 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{poemquote|Last night I saw upon the stair\nA little man who wasn't there\nHe wasn't there again today\nOh, how I wish he'd go away...}}\n\nIn the [[BBC Radio 1]] special programme ''ChangesNowBowie'', broadcast on 8 January 1997, Bowie was interviewed by Mary Anne Hobbs and was asked about the song. He commented: \"I guess I wrote it because there was a part of myself that I was looking for. Maybe now that I feel more comfortable with the way that I live my life and my mental state (laughs) and my spiritual state whatever, maybe I feel there's some kind of unity now. That song for me always exemplified kind of how you feel when you're young, when you know that there's a piece of yourself that you haven't really put together yet. You have this great searching, this great need to find out who you really are.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Appearances/Radio/1997/0108/radio1-transcript.html |title=ChangesNowBowie Transcript \u2013 Radio 1 |first=Grant |last=Wallace |date=27 June 1999 |accessdate=19 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902074027/http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Appearances/Radio/1997/0108/radio1-transcript.html |archive-date=2 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Other releases by Bowie==\n*\"The Man Who Sold the World\" appeared as the B-side on the American single release of the song  \"[[Space Oddity]]\" (1973 rerelease) and British single \"[[Life on Mars?]]\" (1973).<ref name=\"1973 US single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Space Oddity\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1973|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=US|type=Single liner notes|id=74-0876}}</ref><ref name=\"1973 UK single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Life on Mars?\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1973|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=UK|type=Single liner notes|id=RCA 2316}}</ref> It also appears on various Bowie compilations such as ''[[Sound + Vision (box set)|Sound + Vision]]'' (1989), ''[[The Best of David Bowie 1969/1974]]'' (1997), ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002), ''[[The Platinum Collection (David Bowie album)|The Platinum Collection]]'' (2006), ''[[Nothing Has Changed]]'' (2014), and ''[[Bowie Legacy]]'' (2016).\n*On 15 December 1979, Bowie recorded the song for a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' broadcast, with [[Klaus Nomi]] and [[Joey Arias]]. A portion of this show is included in the film ''[[The Nomi Song]]'', and the full performance was included in the touring exhibit ''[[David Bowie Is]]''.\n*A new [[drum n' bass]] studio version of the song was recorded by Bowie and mixed by [[Brian Eno]] and  appears as a B-side on the CD single \"[[Strangers When We Meet (David Bowie song)|Strangers When We Meet]]\" (1995). This version also appears on the bonus disc that followed some versions of ''[[Outside (David Bowie album)|Outside]] \u2013 Version 3''. It was this arrangement that appeared in Bowie's 2016 stage musical, ''[[Lazarus (musical)|Lazarus]]''.\n* Bowie's 25 June 2000 performance of the song at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] was released on ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"Collins Pitchfork\">{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Sean T. |title=David Bowie: ''Glastonbury 2000'' Album Review |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-glastonbury-2000/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=5 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711093411/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-glastonbury-2000/ |archive-date=11 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*A live version recorded at BBC Radio Theatre, London, on 27 June 2000 was released on the bonus disc accompanying the first releases of ''[[Bowie at the Beeb]]'' (2000).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Bowie at the Beeb: The Best of the BBC Radio Sessions 68\u201372'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/bowie-at-the-beeb-the-best-of-the-bbc-radio-sessions-bonus-disc-mw0000619751 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702122107/https://www.allmusic.com/album/bowie-at-the-beeb-the-best-of-the-bbc-radio-sessions-bonus-disc-mw0000619751 |archive-date=2 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* A November 2003 live performance from the [[A Reality Tour|Reality Tour]] is featured on the concert film ''[[A Reality Tour (film)|A Reality Tour]]'' (2004), as well as the live album ''[[A Reality Tour (album)|A Reality Tour]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-reality-tour-mw0001401403|title=''A Reality Tour'' \u2013 Davis Bowie|website=[[AllMusic]]|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|accessdate=11 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818165655/http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-reality-tour-mw0001401403|archive-date=18 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* A remastered version of the song appears in the box set ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' (2015).\n* A previously unreleased acoustic version was released on what would have been Bowie's 73rd birthday (2020).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blisten |first1=Jon |title=Hear David Bowie's Airy, Previously Unreleased Version of 'The Man Who Sold the World' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/david-bowie-man-who-sold-the-world-previously-unreleased-935000/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=25 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114170552/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/david-bowie-man-who-sold-the-world-previously-unreleased-935000/ |archivedate=14 January 2020 |date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nAccording to Kevin Cann:{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=210}}\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 lead vocals, acoustic guitar\n*[[Mick Ronson]] \u2013 electric guitar\n*[[Tony Visconti]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Mick Woodmansey|Woody Woodmansey]] \u2013 drums, [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n*Ralph Mace \u2013 [[Moog synthesiser]]\n\n==Lulu version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Man Who Sold the World\n| cover      = File:Themanwhosoldtheworld.png\n| caption    = A-side label of the UK single\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Watch That Man]]\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|1974|01|11}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = July 1973\n| studio     = [[Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville]], [[H\u00e9rouville]], France\n| genre      =\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n| writer     = [[David Bowie]]\n| producer   = \n*David Bowie\n*[[Mick Ronson]]\n| prev_title = Make Believe World\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = The Man with the Golden Gun\n| next_year  = 1974\n}}\n\nThe song was covered by the Scottish singer [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] in 1974, who, according to biographer David Buckley, performed it in \"a sleazy, almost [[Cabaret#German-speaking cabaret|Berlin cabaret]] style\".{{sfn|Buckley|1999|p=196}} Lulu would recall Bowie inviting her to a concert he gave after which he met her in his hotel room saying: \"I want to make an [[motherfucker|MF]] of a record with you [because] you're a great singer.\" Lulu \u2013 \"I didn't think it would happen but [Bowie] followed up two days later. He was \u00fcbercool at the time and I just wanted to be led by him. I loved everything he did. I didn't think 'The Man Who Sold the World' was the greatest song for my voice, but it was such a strong song in itself. I had no idea what it was about. In the studio Bowie kept telling me to smoke more cigarettes, to give my voice a certain quality.\"{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=228}} Bowie produced the Lulu recording of \"The Man Who Sold the World\" with [[Mick Ronson]] during the July 1973 ''[[Pin Ups]]'' sessions and also contributed guitar, [[saxophone]] and backing vocals. The remainder of the band included Ronson on guitar, [[Trevor Bolder]] on bass, [[Mike Garson]] on piano, and [[Aynsley Dunbar]] on drums.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=118}}\n\nLulu's version of \"The Man Who Sold the World\" was released as a [[music single|single]] on 11 January 1974 by [[Polydor Records]] (as 2001 490), with a cover Bowie's ''[[Aladdin Sane]]'' track \"[[Watch That Man]]\" as the B-side.<ref name=\"Lulu single liner notes\" /> Having been introduced by Lulu on the ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' broadcast on 10 January 1974, the track only made its Top 50 debut (at No. 27) on the [[UK Singles Chart]] dated 26 January 1974 following a reprise performance by Lulu on ''Top of the Pops'' two days earlier on 24 January 1974, with a third ''Top of the Pops'' performance by Lulu on 7 February 1974 broadcast facilitating a boost from No. 13 to No. 5 on the chart dated 9 February 1974. In her ''Top of the Pops'' performances in support of \"The Man Who Sold the World\", Lulu has been characterised as \"dressed and sounding exactly like a diminutive Bowie\".<ref name=\"Who Was That Man: a present for Mr Oscar Wilde\">{{cite book| first=Neil| last=Bartlett| year=1988| title=Who Was That Man: a present for Mr Oscar Wilde| publisher=Serpent's Tail| location=London| pages=[https://archive.org/details/whowasthatmanpre00bart/page/244 244]| isbn=978-1-85242-123-6| url=https://archive.org/details/whowasthatmanpre00bart/page/244}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\nAll songs written by [[David Bowie]].<ref name=\"Lulu single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"The Man Who Sold the World\"''|others=[[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]]|year=1974|publisher=[[Polydor Records]]|location=UK|type=Single liner notes|id=2001 490}}</ref>\n\n# \"The Man Who Sold the World\" \u2013 3:58\n# \"[[Watch That Man]]\" \u2013 5:11\n\n===Chart positions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1974)\n!Position\n|-\n|Belgian Singles Chart ''([[Ultratop]])''<ref name=\"LuluChart\">[http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Lulu&titel=The+Man+Who+Sold+The+World&cat=s Lulu \u2013 The Man Who Sold the World \u2013 peak chart positions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110085413/http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Lulu&titel=The+Man+Who+Sold+The+World&cat=s |date=10 November 2013 }} dutchcharts.com. Retrieved 3 November 2013.</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 24\n|-\n|Netherlands Singles Chart<ref name=\"LuluChart\"/>\n|align=\"center\"| 10\n|-\n|[[Irish Singles Chart]]<ref>[http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement Lulu \u2013 Irish Singles Chart peak positions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411175913/http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |date=11 April 2016 }} irishcharts.ie. Retrieved 3 November 2013.</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 8\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart]] ''([[Official Chart Company]])''<ref>[http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/lulu/ Lulu \u2013 UK Singles Chart peak positions] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130106001249/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/lulu/ |date=6 January 2013 }} officialcharts.com. Retrieved 3 November 2013.</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 3\n|}\n\n===Personnel===\nAccording to [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]]:{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=118}}\n*[[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] \u2013 lead vocals\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 saxophone, backing vocals\n*[[Mick Ronson]] \u2013 guitars\n*[[Trevor Bolder]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Mike Garson]] \u2013 piano\n*[[Aynsley Dunbar]] \u2013 drums\n\n==Nirvana version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = The Man Who Sold the World\n| cover    = The Man Who Sold the World (Nirvana).jpg\n| caption  = \"The Man Who Sold the World\" promo single from the album ''MTV unplugged in New York''\n| alt      =\n| type     = promo\n| artist   = [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n| album    = [[MTV Unplugged in New York]]\n| released = {{Start date|1995}}\n| recorded = 18 November 1993\n| studio   = [[Sony Music Studios|Sony Music]], New York City\n| genre    = \n| length   = {{Duration|m=4|s=20}}\n| label    = [[DGC Records|DGC]]\n| writer   = [[David Bowie]]\n| producer = \n*[[Alex Coletti]]\n*[[Scott Litt]]\n*Nirvana\n| prev_title = [[Polly (Nirvana song)|Polly]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Where Did You Sleep Last Night#Mark Lanegan/Nirvana|Where Did You Sleep Last Night]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n| misc        = {{Extra track listing\n | album      = [[MTV Unplugged in New York]]\n | type       = song\n | tracks   = {{MTV Unplugged in New York tracks}}\n }}\n{{Audio sample\n | type = song\n | file = The Man Who Sold The World.ogg\n}}\n{{External music video|type=song|{{Youtube|fregObNcHC8|\"The Man Who Sold the World\"}}}}\n}}\n\nIn his journals, [[Kurt Cobain]] of the American [[grunge]] band [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] ranked the album ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' at number 45 in his top 50 favourite albums.<ref>[http://www.nirvanaclub.com/info/nirvinfoa/journals.txt Kurt's Journals \u2013 His Top 50 Albums] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218152501/http://nirvanaclub.com/info/nirvinfoa/journals.txt |date=18 December 2010 }}. http://www.nirvanaclub.com {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614211004/http://www.nirvanaclub.com/ |date=14 June 2010 }}. Retrieved 24 July 2010.</ref> Nirvana recorded a live rendition of the song in 1993 during their ''[[MTV Unplugged]]'' appearance and included it on their ''[[MTV Unplugged in New York]]'' album the following year; the song was also released as a [[promotional single]] for the album<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Baltin |first=Steve |date=January 21, 1995 |title=Pop Singles |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/90s/1995/CB-1995-01-21-OCR-Page-0011.pdf#search=%22nirvana%20the%20man%20who%22 |access-date=May 28, 2019 |page=11}}</ref> and received considerable airplay on [[alternative rock]] radio stations. The ''Unplugged'' cover was also placed into heavy rotation on [[MTV]], peaking at number 3 on MTV's most played videos on 18 February 1995;<ref>{{cite magazine |date=18 February 1995 |title=Billboard Magazine \u2013 Video Monitor |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Billboard-IDX/IDX/90s/1995/BB-1995-02-18-OCR-Page-0036.pdf#search=%22video%20monitor%20nirvana%20man%20who%22 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |location= |publisher= |access-date=5 August 2018}}</ref> it also peaked for two weeks at number 7 on Canada's ''[[Countdown (MuchMusic)|MuchMusic Countdown]]'' in March 1995.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hitsofalldecades.com/chart_hits/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1349&Itemid=52 |title=MUCHMUSIC (CANADA) WEEKLY SINGLE CHARTS FOR 1995 |website=hitsofalldecades.com |accessdate=July 21, 2019}}</ref> Nirvana regularly covered the song during live sets after their ''MTV Unplugged'' performance up till Cobain's death in 1994. In 2002, the song was re-released on Nirvana's [[Nirvana (Nirvana album)|self-titled \"best of\" compilation]].\n\nBowie said of Nirvana's cover: \"I was simply blown away when I found that Kurt Cobain liked my work, and have always wanted to talk to him about his reasons for covering 'The Man Who Sold the World{{'\"}} and that \"it was a good straight forward rendition and sounded somehow very honest. It would have been nice to have worked with him, but just talking with him would have been real cool.\"<ref>[[Kurt St. Thomas|St Thomas, Kurt]] and Smith, Troy. ''Nirvana: The Chosen Rejects''. St Martin's Griffin (2004). pp. 191. {{ISBN|0-312-20663-1}}.</ref> Bowie called Nirvana's cover \"heartfelt\", noting that \"until this [cover], it hadn't occurred to me that I was part of America's musical landscape. I always felt my weight in Europe, but not [in the U.S.].\"<ref>{{citation | title=Cover Story: Bowie, beyond fame and fashion | journal=[[USA Today]] | date=14 September 1995 | pages=D1,2 | last=Gundersen | first=Edna}}</ref> In the wake of its release, Bowie bemoaned the fact that when he performed the number himself, he would encounter \"kids that come up afterwards and say, 'It's cool you're doing a Nirvana song.' And I think, 'Fuck you, you little tosser!{{'\"}}<ref>[[Nicholas Pegg]] (2000). ''The Complete David Bowie'': pp. 138\u2013139.</ref>\n\nAt a pre\u2013[[Grammy Awards]] party on 14 February 2016, surviving Nirvana band members [[Krist Novoselic]], [[Dave Grohl]], and [[Pat Smear]] teamed up with contemporary [[Beck]] to perform \"The Man Who Sold the World\" in tribute to Bowie\u2013who had died the month before\u2014with Beck performing vocals.<ref name=\"Beck\">{{cite news |last=Renshaw |first=David |date=February 15, 2016 |title=Beck and living Nirvana members honour David Bowie at pre-Grammy party |url=http://www.nme.com/news/nirvana/91505 |publisher=[[NME]] |access-date=February 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216092948/http://www.nme.com/news/nirvana/91505 |archive-date=16 February 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> To mark what would have been Kurt Cobain's 50th birthday, in 2017 the [[Phonographic Performance Limited]] released a list of the twenty most-played Nirvana songs on TV and radio in the [[United Kingdom|UK]]; \"The Man Who Sold the World\" ranked at number six.<ref>{{cite news |title=20 most-played Nirvana songs revealed to mark Kurt Cobain\u2019s 50th birthday |url=http://www.planetrock.com/news/rock-news/20-most-played-nirvana-songs-revealed-to-mark-kurt-cobains-50th-birthday/ |publisher=[[Planet Rock (radio station)|Planet Rock]] |access-date=March 3, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222135737/http://www.planetrock.com/news/rock-news/20-most-played-nirvana-songs-revealed-to-mark-kurt-cobains-50th-birthday/ |archive-date=22 February 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA louder electric guitar cover appears on the band's [[Live and Loud (Nirvana video album)|''Live and Loud'']] video album.\n\n===Track listings===\n;US and European promo CD\n#\"The Man Who Sold the World\" (Nirvana)\n\n;Italian jukebox 7\" promo split with [[Aerosmith]] (limited to 500 copies)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nirvana-discography.com/pages/promo/unplugged.html |title=UNPLUGGED IN NEW YORK promos |website=nirvana-discography.com |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506190732/http://www.nirvana-discography.com/pages/promo/unplugged.html |archive-date=6 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n#\"The Man Who Sold the World\" (Performed by Nirvana)\n#\"[[Walk on Water (Aerosmith song)|Walk on Water]]\" (Performed by Aerosmith)\n\n===Charts===\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1995)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|40|artist=Nirvana|song=The Man Who Sold the World}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|22|chartid=7984|accessdate=13 August 2015}}\n|-\n| European Hit Radio Top 40 ([[Music & Media]])<ref>{{cite magazine |title=M & M Charts Airplay EHR Top 40 |url=https://americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-UK/Music/Archive-Music-Media-IDX/IDX/90s/95/MM-1995-02-18-OCR-Page-0033.pdf#search=%22ehr%20top%2040%20nirvana%20the%20man%20who%20sold%20the%20world%22 |magazine=[[Music & Media]] |publisher=Music & Media |date=February 18, 1995 |page=33 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|-\n| Iceland ([[\u00cdslenski listinn|\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?issId=195899&pageId=2724554&lang=is&q=MAN%20THE%20MAN%20WHO%20SOLD%20THE%20WORLD%20NIRVANA|title=\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40 (11.2 '95 \u2013 17.2 '95)|work=[[DV (newspaper)|Dagbla\u00f0i\u00f0 V\u00edsir]]|language=Icelandic|date=February 11, 1995|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Poland ([[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lp3.pl/alpt.phtml?m=12&w=808 |title=Archiwum Listy Przebojow \u2013 Trojki \u2013 Nrivana |website=www.lp3.pl |publisher=[[Polskie Radio]] |access-date=11 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111173911/http://www.lp3.pl/alpt.phtml?m=12&w=808 |archive-date=11 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardalternativesongs|6|artist=Nirvana}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardmainstreamrock|12|artist=Nirvana}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardradiosongs|39|artist=Nirvana}}\n|-\n| US Alternative Top 50 (''[[Radio & Records]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Alternative Top 50 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/90s/95/RR-1995-03-10-OCR-Page-0062.pdf#search=%22nirvana%20the%20man%20who%22 |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |publisher=Radio & Records |date=March 10, 1995 |page=62 |accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n| US Rock Tracks Top 60 (''[[Radio & Records]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Rock Tracks Top 60 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/90s/95/RR-1995-02-24-OCR-Page-0064.pdf#search=%22top%20nirvana%20the%20man%20who%22 |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |publisher=Radio & Records |date=February 24, 1995 |page=64 |accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2012)\n!Position\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKrock|13|date=2012-02-26|accessdate=15 April 2017}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2013)\n!Position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|149|artist=Nirvana|song=The Man Who Sold the World}}\n|}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1995)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US Top Rock  Tracks (''[[Radio & Records]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Top 95 of 95 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/90s/95/RR-1995-12-22-OCR-Page-0086.pdf#search=%22nirvana%20the%20man%20who%22 |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |publisher=Radio & Records |date=December 22, 1995 |page=86 |accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|66\n|}\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:6em;\"| Publication\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\"| Accolade\n! scope=\"col\"| Rank\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1998\n| ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"1\"| United Kingdom\n| ''20 Great Nirvana Songs Picked by the Stars''<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://imgur.com/tT8jwLx |title=The Hit List: 20 Great Nirvana Songs Picked by the Stars |magazine=[[Kerrang!]] |date=July 25, 1998 |issue=709 |page=49 |accessdate=July 21, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 20\n|-\n|}\n\n===Personnel===\n*[[Kurt Cobain]] \u2013 vocals, lead guitar\n*[[Pat Smear]] \u2013 rhythm guitar\n*[[Krist Novoselic]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Dave Grohl]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Lori Goldston]] \u2013 cello\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book|last=Buckley |first=David |year=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |publisher=[[Virgin Books]] |isbn=978-1-85227-784-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cann |first=Kevin |year=2010 |title=Any Day Now \u2013 David Bowie: The London Years: 1947\u20131974 |publisher=Adelita |isbn=978-0-95520-177-6 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Carr |first1=Roy|authorlink1=Roy Carr |last2=Murray |first2=Charles Shaar| authorlink2=Charles Shaar Murray |year=1981 |title=Bowie: An Illustrated Record |publisher=Eel Pie Pub |isbn=978-0-38077-966-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |publisher=[[Titan Books]] |edition=7th |location=London |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-78565-365-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Spitz |first=Marc |author-link1=Marc Spitz |title=Bowie: A Biography |publisher=[[Crown Publishing Group]] |year=2009  |isbn=978-0-307-71699-6|title-link=Bowie: A Biography |location=New York |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|fregObNcHC8|\"The Man Who Sold the World\" cover by Nirvana Official music video (Live at MTV Unplugged)}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|the-man-who-sold-the-world}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n{{Lulu}}\n{{Nirvana (band)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Man Who Sold The World, The}}\n[[Category:1970 songs]]\n[[Category:1974 singles]]\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:Lulu (singer) songs]]\n[[Category:Nirvana (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Tony Visconti]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1970 single by David Bowie}}\n{{about|the song|the album|The Man Who Sold the World (album)}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = The Man Who Sold the World\n| cover    = File:Spaceoddity.png\n| caption  = 1973 US picture sleeve\n| alt      =\n| type     = Single\n| artist   = [[David Bowie]]\n| album    = [[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]\n| A-side   = {{Unbulleted list|\"[[Life on Mars (song)|Life on Mars?]]\" (UK)|\"[[Space Oddity]]\" (US)}}\n| released = \n*{{Start date|1970|11|04|df=y}} (US)\n*April 1971 (UK)<br>22 June 1973 (US and UK reissue)\n| recorded = 4 & 22 May 1970 \n| studio   = [[Trident Studios|Trident]] & [[Advision Studios|Advision]], London\n| genre    = [[Hard rock]]\n| length   = {{Duration|m=3|s=55}}\n| label    = [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]<br>[[RCA Records|RCA]] (1973 reissue)\n| writer   = David Bowie\n| producer = [[Tony Visconti]]\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   = File:David-bowie-the-man-who-sold-the-world-rca-s.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Picture sleeve for the 1983 UK reissue\n}}\n}}\n\"'''The Man Who Sold the World'''\" is a song written and performed by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]]. The title track of Bowie's [[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|third album]], it was released in November 1970 in the US and in April 1971 in the UK. The song has been covered by a number of other artists, notably by [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]], who had a UK No. 3 hit with her version in 1974; by [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], whose 1993 performance of the song for the television program ''[[MTV Unplugged]]'' introduced it to a new audience; and by [[Midge Ure]], whose 1982 cover of the song was featured in the 2015 video game ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain]]'' because the game itself features the song's main theme of doppelg\u00e4ngers.\n\nThe song was reworked by Bowie, featuring atmospheric synths, a new bassline, techno-style drums and a notably darker mood, for performances in concerts from 1995 to 1997, including the [[1995 MTV Europe Music Awards]]. Bowie later returned to playing the original version in the 2000s.\n\n==Recording==\nThe backing track for \"The Man Who Sold the World\" was recorded at [[Trident Studios]] in London on 4 May 1970, along with other album track \"Running Gun Blues\". At this point, the track was recorded under the working title \"Saviour Machine\" and did not contain the title phrase.{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=191\u2013192}} According to producer [[Tony Visconti]], Bowie recorded his vocal on 22 May at [[Advision Studios]], the final day of mixing for the album which, when traveling to Advision, Bowie had intended to name ''Metrobolist'', an homage to [[Fritz Lang]]'s 1927 film ''[[Metropolis (1927 film)|Metropolis]]''.{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=193}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=316}} Bowie's last-minute addition frustrated Visconti, who recalled in 1977: \"This was the beginning of [Bowie's] new style of writing \u2013 'I can't be bothered until I have to'. When it was finished, on the last day of the last mix, I remember telling David, 'I've had it, I can't work like this anymore \u2013 I'm through...David was very disappointed.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|pp=193\u2013194}} This frustration was mostly due in part to his dissatisfaction with the recording sessions: he was mostly in charge of budget and production, as well as maintaining Bowie's interest in the project. Bowie later told [[BBC Radio 1]]'s Stuart Grundy in 1976: \"It was a nightmare, that album. I hated the actual process of making it.\"{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=210}}\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe person in the song has an encounter with a kind of [[doppelg\u00e4nger]], as suggested in the second chorus where \"I never lost control\" is replaced with \"We never lost control\".<ref>{{Cite book| contribution = Future Legends: David Bowie and Science Fiction| last = King| first = Maureen| editor-last = Morrison| editor-first = Michael A.| title = Trajectories of the Fantastic: Selected Essays from the Fourteenth International Conference on the Fantastic in the Arts| publisher = Greenwood| year = 1997| location = Westport, CT| page = 131 }}</ref> Beyond this, the episode is unexplained: as James E. Perone wrote,\n\n{{quote|Bowie encounters the title character, but it is not clear just what the phrase means, or exactly who this man is.&nbsp;... The main thing that the song does is to paint \u2013 however elusively \u2013 the title character as another example of the societal outcasts who populate the album.<ref>{{Cite book| last = Perone| first = James E.| title = The Words and Music of David Bowie| publisher = Praeger| year = 2007| location = Westport, Connecticut| pages = 15\u201316}}</ref>}}\n\nIn common with a number of tracks on the album, the song's themes have been compared to the [[Horror fiction|horror]]-[[fantasy]] works of [[H. P. Lovecraft]].{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=38}} The lyrics are also cited as reflecting Bowie's concerns with splintered or multiple personalities, and are believed to have been partially inspired by the poem \"[[Antigonish (poem)|Antigonish]]\" by [[William Hughes Mearns]]:{{sfn|Buckley|1999|p=100}}<ref name=\"Thompson AllMusic\">{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Dave |title=\"The Man Who Sold the World\" \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/the-man-who-sold-the-world-mt0052219335 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{poemquote|Last night I saw upon the stair\nA little man who wasn't there\nHe wasn't there again today\nOh, how I wish he'd go away...}}\n\nIn the [[BBC Radio 1]] special programme ''ChangesNowBowie'', broadcast on 8 January 1997, Bowie was interviewed by Mary Anne Hobbs and was asked about the song. He commented: \"I guess I wrote it because there was a part of myself that I was looking for. Maybe now that I feel more comfortable with the way that I live my life and my mental state (laughs) and my spiritual state whatever, maybe I feel there's some kind of unity now. That song for me always exemplified kind of how you feel when you're young, when you know that there's a piece of yourself that you haven't really put together yet. You have this great searching, this great need to find out who you really are.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Appearances/Radio/1997/0108/radio1-transcript.html |title=ChangesNowBowie Transcript \u2013 Radio 1 |first=Grant |last=Wallace |date=27 June 1999 |accessdate=19 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902074027/http://www.teenagewildlife.com/Appearances/Radio/1997/0108/radio1-transcript.html |archive-date=2 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Other releases by Bowie==\n*\"The Man Who Sold the World\" appeared as the B-side on the American single release of the song  \"[[Space Oddity]]\" (1973 rerelease) and British single \"[[Life on Mars?]]\" (1973).<ref name=\"1973 US single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Space Oddity\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1973|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=US|type=Single liner notes|id=74-0876}}</ref><ref name=\"1973 UK single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Life on Mars?\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1973|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=UK|type=Single liner notes|id=RCA 2316}}</ref> It also appears on various Bowie compilations such as ''[[Sound + Vision (box set)|Sound + Vision]]'' (1989), ''[[The Best of David Bowie 1969/1974]]'' (1997), ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002), ''[[The Platinum Collection (David Bowie album)|The Platinum Collection]]'' (2006), ''[[Nothing Has Changed]]'' (2014), and ''[[Bowie Legacy]]'' (2016).\n*On 15 December 1979, Bowie recorded the song for a ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' broadcast, with [[Klaus Nomi]] and [[Joey Arias]]. A portion of this show is included in the film ''[[The Nomi Song]]'', and the full performance was included in the touring exhibit ''[[David Bowie Is]]''.\n*A new [[drum n' bass]] studio version of the song was recorded by Bowie and mixed by [[Brian Eno]] and  appears as a B-side on the CD single \"[[Strangers When We Meet (David Bowie song)|Strangers When We Meet]]\" (1995). This version also appears on the bonus disc that followed some versions of ''[[Outside (David Bowie album)|Outside]] \u2013 Version 3''. It was this arrangement that appeared in Bowie's 2016 stage musical, ''[[Lazarus (musical)|Lazarus]]''.\n* Bowie's 25 June 2000 performance of the song at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] was released on ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"Collins Pitchfork\">{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Sean T. |title=David Bowie: ''Glastonbury 2000'' Album Review |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-glastonbury-2000/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=5 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711093411/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-glastonbury-2000/ |archive-date=11 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*A live version recorded at BBC Radio Theatre, London, on 27 June 2000 was released on the bonus disc accompanying the first releases of ''[[Bowie at the Beeb]]'' (2000).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Bowie at the Beeb: The Best of the BBC Radio Sessions 68\u201372'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/bowie-at-the-beeb-the-best-of-the-bbc-radio-sessions-bonus-disc-mw0000619751 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702122107/https://www.allmusic.com/album/bowie-at-the-beeb-the-best-of-the-bbc-radio-sessions-bonus-disc-mw0000619751 |archive-date=2 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* A November 2003 live performance from the [[A Reality Tour|Reality Tour]] is featured on the concert film ''[[A Reality Tour (film)|A Reality Tour]]'' (2004), as well as the live album ''[[A Reality Tour (album)|A Reality Tour]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-reality-tour-mw0001401403|title=''A Reality Tour'' \u2013 Davis Bowie|website=[[AllMusic]]|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|accessdate=11 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818165655/http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-reality-tour-mw0001401403|archive-date=18 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* A remastered version of the song appears in the box set ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' (2015).\n* A previously unreleased acoustic version was released on what would have been Bowie's 73rd birthday (2020).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blisten |first1=Jon |title=Hear David Bowie's Airy, Previously Unreleased Version of 'The Man Who Sold the World' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/david-bowie-man-who-sold-the-world-previously-unreleased-935000/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=25 January 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114170552/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/david-bowie-man-who-sold-the-world-previously-unreleased-935000/ |archivedate=14 January 2020 |date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nAccording to Kevin Cann:{{sfn|Cann|2010|p=210}}\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 lead vocals, acoustic guitar\n*[[Mick Ronson]] \u2013 electric guitar\n*[[Tony Visconti]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Mick Woodmansey|Woody Woodmansey]] \u2013 drums, [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n*Ralph Mace \u2013 [[Moog synthesiser]]\n\n==Lulu version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Man Who Sold the World\n| cover      = File:Themanwhosoldtheworld.png\n| caption    = A-side label of the UK single\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Watch That Man]]\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|1974|01|11}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = July 1973\n| studio     = [[Ch\u00e2teau d'H\u00e9rouville]], [[H\u00e9rouville]], France\n| genre      =\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Polydor Records|Polydor]]\n| writer     = [[David Bowie]]\n| producer   = \n*David Bowie\n*[[Mick Ronson]]\n| prev_title = Make Believe World\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = The Man with the Golden Gun\n| next_year  = 1974\n}}\n\nThe song was covered by the Scottish singer [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] in 1974, who, according to biographer David Buckley, performed it in \"a sleazy, almost [[Cabaret#German-speaking cabaret|Berlin cabaret]] style\".{{sfn|Buckley|1999|p=196}} Lulu would recall Bowie inviting her to a concert he gave after which he met her in his hotel room saying: \"I want to make an [[motherfucker|MF]] of a record with you [because] you're a great singer.\" Lulu \u2013 \"I didn't think it would happen but [Bowie] followed up two days later. He was \u00fcbercool at the time and I just wanted to be led by him. I loved everything he did. I didn't think 'The Man Who Sold the World' was the greatest song for my voice, but it was such a strong song in itself. I had no idea what it was about. In the studio Bowie kept telling me to smoke more cigarettes, to give my voice a certain quality.\"{{sfn|Spitz|2009|p=228}} Bowie produced the Lulu recording of \"The Man Who Sold the World\" with [[Mick Ronson]] during the July 1973 ''[[Pin Ups]]'' sessions and also contributed guitar, [[saxophone]] and backing vocals. The remainder of the band included Ronson on guitar, [[Trevor Bolder]] on bass, [[Mike Garson]] on piano, and [[Aynsley Dunbar]] on drums.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=118}}\n\nLulu's version of \"The Man Who Sold the World\" was released as a [[music single|single]] on 11 January 1974 by [[Polydor Records]] (as 2001 490), with a cover Bowie's ''[[Aladdin Sane]]'' track \"[[Watch That Man]]\" as the B-side.<ref name=Lulu single liner notes\" /> Having been introduced by Lulu on the ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' broadcast on 10 January 1974, the track only made its Top 50 debut (at No. 27) on the [[UK Singles Chart]] dated 26 January 1974 following a reprise performance by Lulu on ''Top of the Pops'' two days earlier on 24 January 1974, with a third ''Top of the Pops'' performance by Lulu on 7 February 1974 broadcast facilitating a boost from No. 13 to No. 5 on the chart dated 9 February 1974. In her ''Top of the Pops'' performances in support of \"The Man Who Sold the World\", Lulu has been characterised as \"dressed and sounding exactly like a diminutive Bowie\".<ref name=\"Who Was That Man: a present for Mr Oscar Wilde\">{{cite book| first=Neil| last=Bartlett| year=1988| title=Who Was That Man: a present for Mr Oscar Wilde| publisher=Serpent's Tail| location=London| pages=[https://archive.org/details/whowasthatmanpre00bart/page/244 244]| isbn=978-1-85242-123-6| url=https://archive.org/details/whowasthatmanpre00bart/page/244}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\nAll songs written by [[David Bowie]].<ref name=Lulu single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"The Man Who Sold the World\"''|others=[[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]]|year=1974|publisher=[[Polydor Records]]|location=UK|type=Single liner notes|id=2001 490}}</ref>\n\n# \"The Man Who Sold the World\" \u2013 3:58\n# \"[[Watch That Man]]\" \u2013 5:11\n\n===Chart positions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1974)\n!Position\n|-\n|Belgian Singles Chart ''([[Ultratop]])''<ref name=\"LuluChart\">[http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Lulu&titel=The+Man+Who+Sold+The+World&cat=s Lulu \u2013 The Man Who Sold the World \u2013 peak chart positions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110085413/http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Lulu&titel=The+Man+Who+Sold+The+World&cat=s |date=10 November 2013 }} dutchcharts.com. Retrieved 3 November 2013.</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 24\n|-\n|Netherlands Singles Chart<ref name=\"LuluChart\"/>\n|align=\"center\"| 10\n|-\n|[[Irish Singles Chart]]<ref>[http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement Lulu \u2013 Irish Singles Chart peak positions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411175913/http://www.irishcharts.ie/search/placement |date=11 April 2016 }} irishcharts.ie. Retrieved 3 November 2013.</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 8\n|-\n|[[UK Singles Chart]] ''([[Official Chart Company]])''<ref>[http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/lulu/ Lulu \u2013 UK Singles Chart peak positions] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130106001249/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/lulu/ |date=6 January 2013 }} officialcharts.com. Retrieved 3 November 2013.</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 3\n|}\n\n===Personnel===\nAccording to [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]]:{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|p=118}}\n*[[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] \u2013 lead vocals\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 saxophone, backing vocals\n*[[Mick Ronson]] \u2013 guitars\n*[[Trevor Bolder]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Mike Garson]] \u2013 piano\n*[[Aynsley Dunbar]] \u2013 drums\n\n==Nirvana version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = The Man Who Sold the World\n| cover    = The Man Who Sold the World (Nirvana).jpg\n| caption  = \"The Man Who Sold the World\" promo single from the album ''MTV unplugged in New York''\n| alt      =\n| type     = promo\n| artist   = [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n| album    = [[MTV Unplugged in New York]]\n| released = {{Start date|1995}}\n| recorded = 18 November 1993\n| studio   = [[Sony Music Studios|Sony Music]], New York City\n| genre    = \n| length   = {{Duration|m=4|s=20}}\n| label    = [[DGC Records|DGC]]\n| writer   = [[David Bowie]]\n| producer = \n*[[Alex Coletti]]\n*[[Scott Litt]]\n*Nirvana\n| prev_title = [[Polly (Nirvana song)|Polly]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Where Did You Sleep Last Night#Mark Lanegan/Nirvana|Where Did You Sleep Last Night]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n| misc        = {{Extra track listing\n | album      = [[MTV Unplugged in New York]]\n | type       = song\n | tracks   = {{MTV Unplugged in New York tracks}}\n }}\n{{Audio sample\n | type = song\n | file = The Man Who Sold The World.ogg\n}}\n{{External music video|type=song|{{Youtube|fregObNcHC8|\"The Man Who Sold the World\"}}}}\n}}\n\nIn his journals, [[Kurt Cobain]] of the American [[grunge]] band [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] ranked the album ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold the World]]'' at number 45 in his top 50 favourite albums.<ref>[http://www.nirvanaclub.com/info/nirvinfoa/journals.txt Kurt's Journals \u2013 His Top 50 Albums] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218152501/http://nirvanaclub.com/info/nirvinfoa/journals.txt |date=18 December 2010 }}. http://www.nirvanaclub.com {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614211004/http://www.nirvanaclub.com/ |date=14 June 2010 }}. Retrieved 24 July 2010.</ref> Nirvana recorded a live rendition of the song in 1993 during their ''[[MTV Unplugged]]'' appearance and included it on their ''[[MTV Unplugged in New York]]'' album the following year; the song was also released as a [[promotional single]] for the album<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Baltin |first=Steve |date=January 21, 1995 |title=Pop Singles |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/90s/1995/CB-1995-01-21-OCR-Page-0011.pdf#search=%22nirvana%20the%20man%20who%22 |access-date=May 28, 2019 |page=11}}</ref> and received considerable airplay on [[alternative rock]] radio stations. The ''Unplugged'' cover was also placed into heavy rotation on [[MTV]], peaking at number 3 on MTV's most played videos on 18 February 1995;<ref>{{cite magazine |date=18 February 1995 |title=Billboard Magazine \u2013 Video Monitor |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Billboard-IDX/IDX/90s/1995/BB-1995-02-18-OCR-Page-0036.pdf#search=%22video%20monitor%20nirvana%20man%20who%22 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |location= |publisher= |access-date=5 August 2018}}</ref> it also peaked for two weeks at number 7 on Canada's ''[[Countdown (MuchMusic)|MuchMusic Countdown]]'' in March 1995.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hitsofalldecades.com/chart_hits/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1349&Itemid=52 |title=MUCHMUSIC (CANADA) WEEKLY SINGLE CHARTS FOR 1995 |website=hitsofalldecades.com |accessdate=July 21, 2019}}</ref> Nirvana regularly covered the song during live sets after their ''MTV Unplugged'' performance up till Cobain's death in 1994. In 2002, the song was re-released on Nirvana's [[Nirvana (Nirvana album)|self-titled \"best of\" compilation]].\n\nBowie said of Nirvana's cover: \"I was simply blown away when I found that Kurt Cobain liked my work, and have always wanted to talk to him about his reasons for covering 'The Man Who Sold the World{{'\"}} and that \"it was a good straight forward rendition and sounded somehow very honest. It would have been nice to have worked with him, but just talking with him would have been real cool.\"<ref>[[Kurt St. Thomas|St Thomas, Kurt]] and Smith, Troy. ''Nirvana: The Chosen Rejects''. St Martin's Griffin (2004). pp. 191. {{ISBN|0-312-20663-1}}.</ref> Bowie called Nirvana's cover \"heartfelt\", noting that \"until this [cover], it hadn't occurred to me that I was part of America's musical landscape. I always felt my weight in Europe, but not [in the U.S.].\"<ref>{{citation | title=Cover Story: Bowie, beyond fame and fashion | journal=[[USA Today]] | date=14 September 1995 | pages=D1,2 | last=Gundersen | first=Edna}}</ref> In the wake of its release, Bowie bemoaned the fact that when he performed the number himself, he would encounter \"kids that come up afterwards and say, 'It's cool you're doing a Nirvana song.' And I think, 'Fuck you, you little tosser!{{'\"}}<ref>[[Nicholas Pegg]] (2000). ''The Complete David Bowie'': pp. 138\u2013139.</ref>\n\nAt a pre\u2013[[Grammy Awards]] party on 14 February 2016, surviving Nirvana band members [[Krist Novoselic]], [[Dave Grohl]], and [[Pat Smear]] teamed up with contemporary [[Beck]] to perform \"The Man Who Sold the World\" in tribute to Bowie\u2013who had died the month before\u2014with Beck performing vocals.<ref name=\"Beck\">{{cite news |last=Renshaw |first=David |date=February 15, 2016 |title=Beck and living Nirvana members honour David Bowie at pre-Grammy party |url=http://www.nme.com/news/nirvana/91505 |publisher=[[NME]] |access-date=February 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216092948/http://www.nme.com/news/nirvana/91505 |archive-date=16 February 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> To mark what would have been Kurt Cobain's 50th birthday, in 2017 the [[Phonographic Performance Limited]] released a list of the twenty most-played Nirvana songs on TV and radio in the [[United Kingdom|UK]]; \"The Man Who Sold the World\" ranked at number six.<ref>{{cite news |title=20 most-played Nirvana songs revealed to mark Kurt Cobain\u2019s 50th birthday |url=http://www.planetrock.com/news/rock-news/20-most-played-nirvana-songs-revealed-to-mark-kurt-cobains-50th-birthday/ |publisher=[[Planet Rock (radio station)|Planet Rock]] |access-date=March 3, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222135737/http://www.planetrock.com/news/rock-news/20-most-played-nirvana-songs-revealed-to-mark-kurt-cobains-50th-birthday/ |archive-date=22 February 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA louder electric guitar cover appears on the band's [[Live and Loud (Nirvana video album)|''Live and Loud'']] video album.\n\n===Track listings===\n;US and European promo CD\n#\"The Man Who Sold the World\" (Nirvana)\n\n;Italian jukebox 7\" promo split with [[Aerosmith]] (limited to 500 copies)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nirvana-discography.com/pages/promo/unplugged.html |title=UNPLUGGED IN NEW YORK promos |website=nirvana-discography.com |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190506190732/http://www.nirvana-discography.com/pages/promo/unplugged.html |archive-date=6 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n#\"The Man Who Sold the World\" (Performed by Nirvana)\n#\"[[Walk on Water (Aerosmith song)|Walk on Water]]\" (Performed by Aerosmith)\n\n===Charts===\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1995)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|40|artist=Nirvana|song=The Man Who Sold the World}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|22|chartid=7984|accessdate=13 August 2015}}\n|-\n| European Hit Radio Top 40 ([[Music & Media]])<ref>{{cite magazine |title=M & M Charts Airplay EHR Top 40 |url=https://americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-UK/Music/Archive-Music-Media-IDX/IDX/90s/95/MM-1995-02-18-OCR-Page-0033.pdf#search=%22ehr%20top%2040%20nirvana%20the%20man%20who%20sold%20the%20world%22 |magazine=[[Music & Media]] |publisher=Music & Media |date=February 18, 1995 |page=33 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|-\n| Iceland ([[\u00cdslenski listinn|\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?issId=195899&pageId=2724554&lang=is&q=MAN%20THE%20MAN%20WHO%20SOLD%20THE%20WORLD%20NIRVANA|title=\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40 (11.2 '95 \u2013 17.2 '95)|work=[[DV (newspaper)|Dagbla\u00f0i\u00f0 V\u00edsir]]|language=Icelandic|date=February 11, 1995|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| Poland ([[Lista Przeboj\u00f3w Programu Trzeciego|LP3]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lp3.pl/alpt.phtml?m=12&w=808 |title=Archiwum Listy Przebojow \u2013 Trojki \u2013 Nrivana |website=www.lp3.pl |publisher=[[Polskie Radio]] |access-date=11 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181111173911/http://www.lp3.pl/alpt.phtml?m=12&w=808 |archive-date=11 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardalternativesongs|6|artist=Nirvana}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardmainstreamrock|12|artist=Nirvana}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardradiosongs|39|artist=Nirvana}}\n|-\n| US Alternative Top 50 (''[[Radio & Records]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Alternative Top 50 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/90s/95/RR-1995-03-10-OCR-Page-0062.pdf#search=%22nirvana%20the%20man%20who%22 |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |publisher=Radio & Records |date=March 10, 1995 |page=62 |accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n| US Rock Tracks Top 60 (''[[Radio & Records]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Rock Tracks Top 60 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/90s/95/RR-1995-02-24-OCR-Page-0064.pdf#search=%22top%20nirvana%20the%20man%20who%22 |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |publisher=Radio & Records |date=February 24, 1995 |page=64 |accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2012)\n!Position\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKrock|13|date=2012-02-26|accessdate=15 April 2017}}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2013)\n!Position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|149|artist=Nirvana|song=The Man Who Sold the World}}\n|}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1995)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n| US Top Rock  Tracks (''[[Radio & Records]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Top 95 of 95 |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/90s/95/RR-1995-12-22-OCR-Page-0086.pdf#search=%22nirvana%20the%20man%20who%22 |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |publisher=Radio & Records |date=December 22, 1995 |page=86 |accessdate=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|66\n|}\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:6em;\"| Publication\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Country\n! scope=\"col\"| Accolade\n! scope=\"col\"| Rank\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1998\n| ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"1\"| United Kingdom\n| ''20 Great 